# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: action-potential
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] An **action potential** (also known as a **nerve impulse** or "**spike**" when in a neuron) is a series of quick changes in voltage across a cell membrane.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] An action potential occurs when the membrane potential of a specific cell rapidly rises and falls.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] This "depolarization" (physically, a reversal of the polarization of the membrane) then causes adjacent locations to similarly depolarize.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Action potentials occur in several types of excitable cells, which include animal cells like neurons and muscle cells, as well as some plant cells.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Certain endocrine cells such as pancreatic beta cells, and certain cells of the anterior pituitary gland are also excitable cells.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] In other types of cells, their main function is to activate intracellular processes.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] In muscle cells, for example, an action potential is the first step in the chain of events leading to contraction.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] In beta cells of the pancreas, they provoke release of insulin.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The temporal sequence of action potentials generated by a neuron is called its "spike train".
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] A neuron that emits an action potential, or nerve impulse, is often said to "fire".
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Action potentials are generated by special types of voltage-gated ion channels embedded in a cell's plasma membrane.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] These channels are shut when the membrane potential is near the (negative) resting potential of the cell, but they rapidly begin to open if the membrane potential increases to a precisely defined threshold voltage, "depolarising" the membrane.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] When the channels open, they allow an inward flow of sodium ions, which makes the interior of the cell more positive, which further raises the (negative) membrane potential.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] This then causes more channels to open, producing a greater electric current across the cell membrane and so on.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The process proceeds explosively until all of the available ion channels are open, resulting in a large upswing in the membrane potential.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The rapid influx of sodium ions causes the polarity of (i.e. the direction of the electric field across) the plasma membrane to reverse, and the ion channels then rapidly inactivate.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] As the sodium channels close, sodium ions can no longer enter the neuron, and they are then actively transported back out of the plasma membrane.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Potassium channels are then activated, and there is an outward current of potassium ions, returning the electrochemical gradient to the resting state.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Because few ions need to pass through to change the potential, the concentrations of ions on either side remain relatively unchanged during this process.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] After an action potential has occurred, there is a transient negative shift, called the afterhyperpolarization.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] In animal cells, there are two primary types of action potentials.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] One type is generated by voltage-gated sodium channels, the other by voltage-gated calcium channels.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Sodium-based action potentials usually last for under one millisecond, but calcium-based action potentials may last for 100 milliseconds or longer.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] In some types of neurons, slow calcium spikes provide the driving force for a long burst of rapidly emitted sodium spikes.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] In cardiac muscle cells, on the other hand, an initial fast sodium spike provides a "primer" to provoke the rapid onset of a calcium spike, which then produces muscle contraction.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Nearly all cell membranes in animals, plants and fungi maintain a voltage difference between the exterior and interior of the cell, called the membrane potential.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] A typical voltage across an animal cell membrane is −70 mV.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] This means that the interior of the cell has a negative voltage relative to the exterior.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] In most types of cells, the membrane potential usually stays fairly constant.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Some types of cells, however, are electrically active in the sense that their voltages fluctuate over time.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] In some types of electrically active cells, including neurons and muscle cells, the voltage fluctuations frequently take the form of a rapid upward (positive) spike followed by a rapid fall.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] These up-and-down cycles are known as *action potentials*.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Their duration varies considerably with the type of cell.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] In mammalian neurons, the entire up-and-down cycle takes only a few thousandths of a second, while in plant cells, an action potential may last as long as several seconds.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The electrical properties of a cell are determined by the structure of its membrane.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] A cell membrane consists of a lipid bilayer of molecules in which larger protein molecules are embedded.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The lipid bilayer is highly resistant to movement of electrically charged ions, so it functions as an insulator.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The large membrane-embedded proteins, in contrast, provide channels through which ions can pass across the membrane.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Action potentials are driven by channel proteins whose configuration switches between closed and open states as a function of the voltage difference between the interior and exterior of the cell.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] These voltage-sensitive proteins are known as voltage-gated ion channels.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] All cells in animal body tissues are electrically polarized – in other words, they maintain a voltage difference across the cell's plasma membrane, known as the membrane potential.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] This electrical polarization results from a complex interplay between protein structures embedded in the membrane called ion pumps and ion channels.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] In neurons, the types of ion channels in the membrane usually vary across different parts of the cell, giving the dendrites, axon, and cell body different electrical properties.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] As a result, some parts of the membrane of a neuron may be excitable (capable of generating action potentials), whereas others are not.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Recent studies have shown that the most excitable part of a neuron is the part after the axon hillock (the point where the axon leaves the cell body), which is called the axonal initial segment, but the axon and cell body are also excitable in most cases.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Each excitable patch of membrane has two important levels of membrane potential: the resting potential, which is the value the membrane potential maintains as long as nothing perturbs the cell, and a higher value called the threshold potential.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] At the axon hillock of a typical neuron, the resting potential is around −70 millivolts (mV) and the threshold potential is around −55 mV.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Synaptic inputs to a neuron cause the membrane to depolarize or hyperpolarize; that is, they cause the membrane potential to rise or fall.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Action potentials are triggered when enough depolarization accumulates to bring the membrane potential up to threshold.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] When an action potential is triggered, the membrane potential abruptly shoots upward and then equally abruptly shoots back downward, often ending below the resting level, where it remains for some period of time.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The shape of the action potential is stereotyped; this means that the rise and fall usually have approximately the same amplitude and time course for all action potentials in a given cell.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] (Exceptions are discussed later in the article) In most neurons, the entire process takes place in about a thousandth of a second.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Many types of neurons emit action potentials constantly at rates of up to 10–100 per second.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] However, some types are much quieter, and may go for minutes or longer without emitting any action potentials.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Action potentials result from the presence in a cell's membrane of special types of voltage-gated ion channels.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] At least one of the conformations creates a channel through the membrane that is permeable to specific types of ions.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The transition between conformations is influenced by the membrane potential.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Thus, a voltage-gated ion channel tends to be open for some values of the membrane potential, and closed for others.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] In most cases, however, the relationship between membrane potential and channel state is probabilistic and involves a time delay.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Ion channels switch between conformations at unpredictable times: The membrane potential determines the rate of transitions and the probability per unit time of each type of transition.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Voltage-gated ion channels are capable of producing action potentials because they can give rise to positive feedback loops: the membrane potential controls the state of the ion channels, and the state of the ion channels controls the membrane potential.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Thus, in some situations, a rise in the membrane potential can cause ion channels to open, thereby causing a further rise in the membrane potential.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] An action potential occurs when this positive feedback cycle proceeds explosively.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The time and amplitude trajectory of the action potential are determined by the biophysical properties of the voltage-gated ion channels that produce it.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Several types of channels capable of producing the positive feedback necessary to generate an action potential do exist.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Voltage-gated sodium channels are responsible for the fast action potentials involved in nerve conduction.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Slower action potentials in muscle cells and some types of neurons are generated by voltage-gated calcium channels.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Each of these types comes in multiple variants, with different voltage sensitivity and different temporal dynamics.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The most intensively studied type of voltage-dependent ion channels comprises the sodium channels involved in fast nerve conduction.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] These are sometimes known as Hodgkin-Huxley sodium channels because they were first characterized by Alan Hodgkin and Andrew Huxley in their Nobel Prize-winning studies of the biophysics of the action potential, but can more conveniently be referred to as *Na*V channels.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] (The "V" stands for "voltage".) An *Na*V channel has three possible states, known as *deactivated*, *activated*, and *inactivated*.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The channel is permeable only to sodium ions when it is in the *activated* state.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] When the membrane potential is low, the channel spends most of its time in the *deactivated* (closed) state.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] If the membrane potential is raised above a certain level, the channel shows increased probability of transitioning to the *activated* (open) state.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The higher the membrane potential the greater the probability of activation.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Once a channel has activated, it will eventually transition to the *inactivated* (closed) state.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] It tends then to stay inactivated for some time, but, if the membrane potential becomes low again, the channel will eventually transition back to the *deactivated* state.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] During an action potential, most channels of this type go through a cycle *deactivated*→*activated*→*inactivated*→*deactivated*.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] This is only the population average behavior, however – an individual channel can in principle make any transition at any time.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] However, the likelihood of a channel's transitioning from the *inactivated* state directly to the *activated* state is very low: A channel in the *inactivated* state is refractory until it has transitioned back to the *deactivated* state.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The outcome of all this is that the kinetics of the *Na*V channels are governed by a transition matrix whose rates are voltage-dependent in a complicated way.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Since these channels themselves play a major role in determining the voltage, the global dynamics of the system can be quite difficult to work out.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Hodgkin and Huxley approached the problem by developing a set of differential equations for the parameters that govern the ion channel states, known as the Hodgkin-Huxley equations.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] These equations have been extensively modified by later research, but form the starting point for most theoretical studies of action potential biophysics.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] As the membrane potential is increased, sodium ion channels open, allowing the entry of sodium ions into the cell.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] This is followed by the opening of potassium ion channels that permit the exit of potassium ions from the cell.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The inward flow of sodium ions increases the concentration of positively charged cations in the cell and causes depolarization, where the potential of the cell is higher than the cell's resting potential.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The sodium channels close at the peak of the action potential, while potassium continues to leave the cell.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The efflux of potassium ions decreases the membrane potential or hyperpolarizes the cell.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] For small voltage increases from rest, the potassium current exceeds the sodium current and the voltage returns to its normal resting value, typically −70 mV.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] However, if the voltage increases past a critical threshold, typically 15 mV higher than the resting value, the sodium current dominates.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] This results in a runaway condition whereby the positive feedback from the sodium current activates even more sodium channels.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Thus, the cell *fires*, producing an action potential.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The frequency at which a neuron elicits action potentials is often referred to as a **firing rate** or **neural firing rate**.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Currents produced by the opening of voltage-gated channels in the course of an action potential are typically significantly larger than the initial stimulating current.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Thus, the amplitude, duration, and shape of the action potential are determined largely by the properties of the excitable membrane and not the amplitude or duration of the stimulus.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] This all-or-nothing property of the action potential sets it apart from graded potentials such as receptor potentials, electrotonic potentials, subthreshold membrane potential oscillations, and synaptic potentials, which scale with the magnitude of the stimulus.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] A variety of action potential types exist in many cell types and cell compartments as determined by the types of voltage-gated channels, leak channels, channel distributions, ionic concentrations, membrane capacitance, temperature, and other factors.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The principal ions involved in an action potential are sodium and potassium cations; sodium ions enter the cell, and potassium ions leave, restoring equilibrium.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Relatively few ions need to cross the membrane for the membrane voltage to change drastically.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The ions exchanged during an action potential, therefore, make a negligible change in the interior and exterior ionic concentrations.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The few ions that do cross are pumped out again by the continuous action of the sodium–potassium pump, which, with other ion transporters, maintains the normal ratio of ion concentrations across the membrane.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Calcium cations and chloride anions are involved in a few types of action potentials, such as the cardiac action potential and the action potential in the single-cell alga *Acetabularia*, respectively.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Although action potentials are generated locally on patches of excitable membrane, the resulting currents can trigger action potentials on neighboring stretches of membrane, precipitating a domino-like propagation.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] In contrast to passive spread of electric potentials (electrotonic potential), action potentials are generated anew along excitable stretches of membrane and propagate without decay.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Myelinated sections of axons are not excitable and do not produce action potentials and the signal is propagated passively as electrotonic potential.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Regularly spaced unmyelinated patches, called the nodes of Ranvier, generate action potentials to boost the signal.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Known as saltatory conduction, this type of signal propagation provides a favorable tradeoff of signal velocity and axon diameter.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Depolarization of axon terminals, in general, triggers the release of neurotransmitter into the synaptic cleft.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] In addition, backpropagating action potentials have been recorded in the dendrites of pyramidal neurons, which are ubiquitous in the neocortex.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] These are thought to have a role in spike-timing-dependent plasticity.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] In the Hodgkin–Huxley membrane capacitance model, the speed of transmission of an action potential was undefined and it was assumed that adjacent areas became depolarized due to released ion interference with neighbouring channels.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Measurements of ion diffusion and radii have since shown this not to be possible.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Moreover, contradictory measurements of entropy changes and timing disputed the capacitance model as acting alone.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Alternatively, Gilbert Ling's adsorption hypothesis, posits that the membrane potential and action potential of a living cell is due to the adsorption of mobile ions onto adsorption sites of cells.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] A neuron's ability to generate and propagate an action potential changes during development.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] How much the membrane potential of a neuron changes as the result of a current impulse is a function of the membrane input resistance.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] As a cell grows, more channels are added to the membrane, causing a decrease in input resistance.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] A mature neuron also undergoes shorter changes in membrane potential in response to synaptic currents.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Neurons from a ferret lateral geniculate nucleus have a longer time constant and larger voltage deflection at P0 than they do at P30.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] One consequence of the decreasing action potential duration is that the fidelity of the signal can be preserved in response to high frequency stimulation.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Immature neurons are more prone to synaptic depression than potentiation after high frequency stimulation.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] In the early development of many organisms, the action potential is actually initially carried by calcium current rather than sodium current.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The opening and closing kinetics of calcium channels during development are slower than those of the voltage-gated sodium channels that will carry the action potential in the mature neurons.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The longer opening times for the calcium channels can lead to action potentials that are considerably slower than those of mature neurons.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Xenopus neurons initially have action potentials that take 60–90 ms.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] During development, this time decreases to 1 ms.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] There are two reasons for this drastic decrease.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] First, the inward current becomes primarily carried by sodium channels.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Second, the delayed rectifier, a potassium channel current, increases to 3.5 times its initial strength.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] In order for the transition from a calcium-dependent action potential to a sodium-dependent action potential to proceed new channels must be added to the membrane.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] If Xenopus neurons are grown in an environment with RNA synthesis or protein synthesis inhibitors that transition is prevented.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Even the electrical activity of the cell itself may play a role in channel expression.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] If action potentials in Xenopus myocytes are blocked, the typical increase in sodium and potassium current density is prevented or delayed.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] This maturation of electrical properties is seen across species.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Xenopus sodium and potassium currents increase drastically after a neuron goes through its final phase of mitosis.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The sodium current density of rat cortical neurons increases by 600% within the first two postnatal weeks.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Several types of cells support an action potential, such as plant cells, muscle cells, and the specialized cells of the heart (in which occurs the cardiac action potential).
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] However, the main excitable cell is the neuron, which also has the simplest mechanism for the action potential.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Neurons are electrically excitable cells composed, in general, of one or more dendrites, a single soma, a single axon and one or more axon terminals.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Dendrites are cellular projections whose primary function is to receive synaptic signals.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Their protrusions, known as dendritic spines, are designed to capture the neurotransmitters released by the presynaptic neuron.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] They have a high concentration of ligand-gated ion channels.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] These spines have a thin neck connecting a bulbous protrusion to the dendrite.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] This ensures that changes occurring inside the spine are less likely to affect the neighboring spines.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The dendritic spine can, with rare exception (see LTP), act as an independent unit.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The dendrites extend from the soma, which houses the nucleus, and many of the "normal" eukaryotic organelles.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Unlike the spines, the surface of the soma is populated by voltage activated ion channels.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] These channels help transmit the signals generated by the dendrites.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Emerging out from the soma is the axon hillock.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] This region is characterized by having a very high concentration of voltage-activated sodium channels.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] In general, it is considered to be the spike initiation zone for action potentials, i.e. the trigger zone.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Multiple signals generated at the spines, and transmitted by the soma all converge here.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Immediately after the axon hillock is the axon.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] This is a thin tubular protrusion traveling away from the soma.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The axon is insulated by a myelin sheath.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Myelin is composed of either Schwann cells (in the peripheral nervous system) or oligodendrocytes (in the central nervous system), both of which are types of glial cells.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Although glial cells are not involved with the transmission of electrical signals, they communicate and provide important biochemical support to neurons.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] To be specific, myelin wraps multiple times around the axonal segment, forming a thick fatty layer that prevents ions from entering or escaping the axon.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] This insulation prevents significant signal decay as well as ensuring faster signal speed.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] This insulation, however, has the restriction that no channels can be present on the surface of the axon.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] There are, therefore, regularly spaced patches of membrane, which have no insulation.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] These nodes of Ranvier can be considered to be "mini axon hillocks", as their purpose is to boost the signal in order to prevent significant signal decay.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] At the furthest end, the axon loses its insulation and begins to branch into several axon terminals.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] These presynaptic terminals, or synaptic boutons, are a specialized area within the axon of the presynaptic cell that contains neurotransmitters enclosed in small membrane-bound spheres called synaptic vesicles.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Before considering the propagation of action potentials along axons and their termination at the synaptic knobs, it is helpful to consider the methods by which action potentials can be initiated at the axon hillock.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The basic requirement is that the membrane voltage at the hillock be raised above the threshold for firing.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] There are several ways in which this depolarization can occur.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Action potentials are most commonly initiated by excitatory postsynaptic potentials from a presynaptic neuron.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Typically, neurotransmitter molecules are released by the presynaptic neuron.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] These neurotransmitters then bind to receptors on the postsynaptic cell.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] This binding opens various types of ion channels.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] This opening has the further effect of changing the local permeability of the cell membrane and, thus, the membrane potential.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] If the binding increases the voltage (depolarizes the membrane), the synapse is excitatory.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] If, however, the binding decreases the voltage (hyperpolarizes the membrane), it is inhibitory.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Whether the voltage is increased or decreased, the change propagates passively to nearby regions of the membrane (as described by the cable equation and its refinements).
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Typically, the voltage stimulus decays exponentially with the distance from the synapse and with time from the binding of the neurotransmitter.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Some fraction of an excitatory voltage may reach the axon hillock and may (in rare cases) depolarize the membrane enough to provoke a new action potential.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] More typically, the excitatory potentials from several synapses must work together at nearly the same time to provoke a new action potential.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Their joint efforts can be thwarted, however, by the counteracting inhibitory postsynaptic potentials.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Neurotransmission can also occur through electrical synapses.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Due to the direct connection between excitable cells in the form of gap junctions, an action potential can be transmitted directly from one cell to the next in either direction.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The free flow of ions between cells enables rapid non-chemical-mediated transmission.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Rectifying channels ensure that action potentials move only in one direction through an electrical synapse.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Electrical synapses are found in all nervous systems, including the human brain, although they are a distinct minority.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The amplitude of an action potential is often thought to be independent of the amount of current that produced it.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] In other words, larger currents do not create larger action potentials.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Therefore, action potentials are said to be all-or-none signals, since either they occur fully or they do not occur at all.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] This is in contrast to receptor potentials, whose amplitudes are dependent on the intensity of a stimulus.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] In both cases, the frequency of action potentials is correlated with the intensity of a stimulus.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] In sensory neurons, an external signal such as pressure, temperature, light, or sound is coupled with the opening and closing of ion channels, which in turn alter the ionic permeabilities of the membrane and its voltage.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] These voltage changes can again be excitatory (depolarizing) or inhibitory (hyperpolarizing) and, in some sensory neurons, their combined effects can depolarize the axon hillock enough to provoke action potentials.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Some examples in humans include the olfactory receptor neuron and Meissner's corpuscle, which are critical for the sense of smell and touch, respectively.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] However, not all sensory neurons convert their external signals into action potentials; some do not even have an axon.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Instead, they may convert the signal into the release of a neurotransmitter, or into continuous graded potentials, either of which may stimulate subsequent neuron(s) into firing an action potential.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] For illustration, in the human ear, hair cells convert the incoming sound into the opening and closing of mechanically gated ion channels, which may cause neurotransmitter molecules to be released.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] In sensory neurons, action potentials result from an external stimulus.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] However, some excitable cells require no such stimulus to fire: They spontaneously depolarize their axon hillock and fire action potentials at a regular rate, like an internal clock.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The voltage traces of such cells are known as pacemaker potentials.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The cardiac pacemaker cells of the sinoatrial node in the heart provide a good example.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Although such pacemaker potentials have a natural rhythm, it can be adjusted by external stimuli; for instance, heart rate can be altered by pharmaceuticals as well as signals from the sympathetic and parasympathetic nerves.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The external stimuli do not cause the cell's repetitive firing, but merely alter its timing.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] In some cases, the regulation of frequency can be more complex, leading to patterns of action potentials, such as bursting.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The course of the action potential can be divided into five parts: the rising phase, the peak phase, the falling phase, the undershoot phase, and the refractory period.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] During the rising phase the membrane potential depolarizes (becomes more positive).
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The point at which depolarization stops is called the peak phase.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] At this stage, the membrane potential reaches a maximum.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Subsequent to this, there is a falling phase.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] During this stage the membrane potential becomes more negative, returning towards resting potential.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The undershoot, or afterhyperpolarization, phase is the period during which the membrane potential temporarily becomes more negatively charged than when at rest (hyperpolarized).
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Finally, the time during which a subsequent action potential is impossible or difficult to fire is called the refractory period, which may overlap with the other phases.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The course of the action potential is determined by two coupled effects.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] First, voltage-sensitive ion channels open and close in response to changes in the membrane voltage *Vm*.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] This changes the membrane's permeability to those ions.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Second, according to the Goldman equation, this change in permeability changes the equilibrium potential *Em*, and, thus, the membrane voltage *Vm*.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Thus, the membrane potential affects the permeability, which then further affects the membrane potential.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] This sets up the possibility for positive feedback, which is a key part of the rising phase of the action potential.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] A complicating factor is that a single ion channel may have multiple internal "gates" that respond to changes in *Vm* in opposite ways, or at different rates.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] For example, although raising *Vm* *opens* most gates in the voltage-sensitive sodium channel, it also *closes* the channel's "inactivation gate", albeit more slowly.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Hence, when *Vm* is raised suddenly, the sodium channels open initially, but then close due to the slower inactivation.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The voltages and currents of the action potential in all of its phases were modeled accurately by Alan Lloyd Hodgkin and Andrew Huxley in 1952, for which they were awarded the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1963.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] However, their model considers only two types of voltage-sensitive ion channels, and makes several assumptions about them, e.g., that their internal gates open and close independently of one another.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] In reality, there are many types of ion channels, and they do not always open and close independently.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] A typical action potential begins at the axon hillock with a sufficiently strong depolarization, e.g., a stimulus that increases *Vm*.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] This depolarization is often caused by the injection of extra sodium cations into the cell; these cations can come from a wide variety of sources, such as chemical synapses, sensory neurons or pacemaker potentials.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] For a neuron at rest, there is a high concentration of sodium and chloride ions in the extracellular fluid compared to the intracellular fluid, while there is a high concentration of potassium ions in the intracellular fluid compared to the extracellular fluid.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The difference in concentrations, which causes ions to move from a high to a low concentration, and electrostatic effects (attraction of opposite charges) are responsible for the movement of ions in and out of the neuron.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The inside of a neuron has a negative charge, relative to the cell exterior, from the movement of K+ out of the cell.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The neuron membrane is more permeable to K+ than to other ions, allowing this ion to selectively move out of the cell, down its concentration gradient.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] This concentration gradient along with potassium leak channels present on the membrane of the neuron causes an efflux of potassium ions making the resting potential close to *E*K ≈ −75 mV.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Since Na+ ions are in higher concentrations outside of the cell, the concentration and voltage differences both drive them into the cell when Na+ channels open.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Depolarization opens both the sodium and potassium channels in the membrane, allowing the ions to flow into and out of the axon, respectively.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] If the depolarization is small (say, increasing *Vm* from −70 mV to −60 mV), the outward potassium current overwhelms the inward sodium current and the membrane repolarizes back to its normal resting potential around −70 mV.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] However, if the depolarization is large enough, the inward sodium current increases more than the outward potassium current and a runaway condition (positive feedback) results: the more inward current there is, the more *Vm* increases, which in turn further increases the inward current.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] A sufficiently strong depolarization (increase in *Vm*) causes the voltage-sensitive sodium channels to open; the increasing permeability to sodium drives *Vm* closer to the sodium equilibrium voltage *E*Na≈ +55 mV.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The increasing voltage in turn causes even more sodium channels to open, which pushes *Vm* still further towards *E*Na.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] This positive feedback continues until the sodium channels are fully open and *Vm* is close to *E*Na.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The sharp rise in *Vm* and sodium permeability correspond to the *rising phase* of the action potential.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The critical threshold voltage for this runaway condition is usually around −45 mV, but it depends on the recent activity of the axon.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] A cell that has just fired an action potential cannot fire another one immediately, since the Na+ channels have not recovered from the inactivated state.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The period during which no new action potential can be fired is called the *absolute refractory period*.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] At longer times, after some but not all of the ion channels have recovered, the axon can be stimulated to produce another action potential, but with a higher threshold, requiring a much stronger depolarization, e.g., to −30 mV.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The period during which action potentials are unusually difficult to evoke is called the *relative refractory period*.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The positive feedback of the rising phase slows and comes to a halt as the sodium ion channels become maximally open.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] At the peak of the action potential, the sodium permeability is maximized and the membrane voltage *Vm* is nearly equal to the sodium equilibrium voltage *E*Na.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] However, the same raised voltage that opened the sodium channels initially also slowly shuts them off, by closing their pores; the sodium channels become *inactivated*.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] This lowers the membrane's permeability to sodium relative to potassium, driving the membrane voltage back towards the resting value.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] At the same time, the raised voltage opens voltage-sensitive potassium channels; the increase in the membrane's potassium permeability drives *Vm* towards *E*K.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Combined, these changes in sodium and potassium permeability cause *Vm* to drop quickly, repolarizing the membrane and producing the "falling phase" of the action potential.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The depolarized voltage opens additional voltage-dependent potassium channels, and some of these do not close right away when the membrane returns to its normal resting voltage.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] In addition, further potassium channels open in response to the influx of calcium ions during the action potential.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The intracellular concentration of potassium ions is transiently unusually low, making the membrane voltage *Vm* even closer to the potassium equilibrium voltage *E*K.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The membrane potential goes below the resting membrane potential.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Hence, there is an undershoot or hyperpolarization, termed an afterhyperpolarization, that persists until the membrane potassium permeability returns to its usual value, restoring the membrane potential to the resting state.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Each action potential is followed by a refractory period, which can be divided into an *absolute refractory period*, during which it is impossible to evoke another action potential, and then a *relative refractory period*, during which a stronger-than-usual stimulus is required.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] These two refractory periods are caused by changes in the state of sodium and potassium channel molecules.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] When closing after an action potential, sodium channels enter an "inactivated" state, in which they cannot be made to open regardless of the membrane potential—this gives rise to the absolute refractory period.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Even after a sufficient number of sodium channels have transitioned back to their resting state, it frequently happens that a fraction of potassium channels remains open, making it difficult for the membrane potential to depolarize, and thereby giving rise to the relative refractory period.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Because the density and subtypes of potassium channels may differ greatly between different types of neurons, the duration of the relative refractory period is highly variable.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The absolute refractory period is largely responsible for the unidirectional propagation of action potentials along axons.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] At any given moment, the patch of axon behind the actively spiking part is refractory, but the patch in front, not having been activated recently, is capable of being stimulated by the depolarization from the action potential.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The action potential generated at the axon hillock propagates as a wave along the axon.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The currents flowing inwards at a point on the axon during an action potential spread out along the axon, and depolarize the adjacent sections of its membrane.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] If sufficiently strong, this depolarization provokes a similar action potential at the neighboring membrane patches.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] This basic mechanism was demonstrated by Alan Lloyd Hodgkin in 1937.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] After crushing or cooling nerve segments and thus blocking the action potentials, he showed that an action potential arriving on one side of the block could provoke another action potential on the other, provided that the blocked segment was sufficiently short.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Once an action potential has occurred at a patch of membrane, the membrane patch needs time to recover before it can fire again.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] At the molecular level, this *absolute refractory period* corresponds to the time required for the voltage-activated sodium channels to recover from inactivation, i.e., to return to their closed state.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] There are many types of voltage-activated potassium channels in neurons.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] On the other hand, all neuronal voltage-activated sodium channels inactivate within several milliseconds during strong depolarization, thus making following depolarization impossible until a substantial fraction of sodium channels have returned to their closed state.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Although it limits the frequency of firing, the absolute refractory period ensures that the action potential moves in only one direction along an axon.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The currents flowing in due to an action potential spread out in both directions along the axon.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] However, only the unfired part of the axon can respond with an action potential; the part that has just fired is unresponsive until the action potential is safely out of range and cannot restimulate that part.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] In the usual orthodromic conduction, the action potential propagates from the axon hillock towards the synaptic knobs (the axonal termini); propagation in the opposite direction—known as antidromic conduction—is very rare.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] However, if a laboratory axon is stimulated in its middle, both halves of the axon are "fresh", i.e., unfired; then two action potentials will be generated, one traveling towards the axon hillock and the other traveling towards the synaptic knobs.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] To enable fast and efficient transduction of electrical signals in the nervous system, certain neuronal axons are covered with myelin sheaths.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Myelin is a multilamellar membrane that enwraps the axon in segments separated by intervals known as nodes of Ranvier.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] It is produced by specialized cells: Schwann cells exclusively in the peripheral nervous system, and oligodendrocytes exclusively in the central nervous system.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Myelin sheath reduces membrane capacitance and increases membrane resistance in the inter-node intervals, thus allowing a fast, saltatory movement of action potentials from node to node.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Myelination is found mainly in vertebrates, but an analogous system has been discovered in a few invertebrates, such as some species of shrimp.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Not all neurons in vertebrates are myelinated; for example, axons of the neurons comprising the autonomic nervous system are not, in general, myelinated.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Myelin prevents ions from entering or leaving the axon along myelinated segments.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] As a general rule, myelination increases the conduction velocity of action potentials and makes them more energy-efficient.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Whether saltatory or not, the mean conduction velocity of an action potential ranges from 1 meter per second (m/s) to over 100 m/s, and, in general, increases with axonal diameter.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Action potentials cannot propagate through the membrane in myelinated segments of the axon.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] However, the current is carried by the cytoplasm, which is sufficient to depolarize the first or second subsequent node of Ranvier.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Instead, the ionic current from an action potential at one node of Ranvier provokes another action potential at the next node; this apparent "hopping" of the action potential from node to node is known as saltatory conduction.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Although the mechanism of saltatory conduction was suggested in 1925 by Ralph Lillie, the first experimental evidence for saltatory conduction came from Ichiji Tasaki and Taiji Takeuchi and from Andrew Huxley and Robert Stämpfli.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] By contrast, in unmyelinated axons, the action potential provokes another in the membrane immediately adjacent, and moves continuously down the axon like a wave.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Myelin has two important advantages: fast conduction speed and energy efficiency.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] For axons larger than a minimum diameter (roughly 1 micrometre), myelination increases the conduction velocity of an action potential, typically tenfold.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Conversely, for a given conduction velocity, myelinated fibers are smaller than their unmyelinated counterparts.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] For example, action potentials move at roughly the same speed (25 m/s) in a myelinated frog axon and an unmyelinated squid giant axon, but the frog axon has a roughly 30-fold smaller diameter and 1000-fold smaller cross-sectional area.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Also, since the ionic currents are confined to the nodes of Ranvier, far fewer ions "leak" across the membrane, saving metabolic energy.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] This saving is a significant selective advantage, since the human nervous system uses approximately 20% of the body's metabolic energy.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The length of axons' myelinated segments is important to the success of saltatory conduction.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] They should be as long as possible to maximize the speed of conduction, but not so long that the arriving signal is too weak to provoke an action potential at the next node of Ranvier.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] In nature, myelinated segments are generally long enough for the passively propagated signal to travel for at least two nodes while retaining enough amplitude to fire an action potential at the second or third node.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Thus, the safety factor of saltatory conduction is high, allowing transmission to bypass nodes in case of injury.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] However, action potentials may end prematurely in certain places where the safety factor is low, even in unmyelinated neurons; a common example is the branch point of an axon, where it divides into two axons.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Some diseases degrade myelin and impair saltatory conduction, reducing the conduction velocity of action potentials.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The most well-known of these is multiple sclerosis, in which the breakdown of myelin impairs coordinated movement.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] The flow of currents within an axon can be described quantitatively by cable theory and its elaborations, such as the compartmental model.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Cable theory was developed in 1855 by Lord Kelvin to model the transatlantic telegraph cable and was shown to be relevant to neurons by Hodgkin and Rushton in 1946.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] In simple cable theory, the neuron is treated as an electrically passive, perfectly cylindrical transmission cable, which can be described by a partial differential equation.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] where *V*(*x*, *t*) is the voltage across the membrane at a time *t* and a position *x* along the length of the neuron, and where λ and τ are the characteristic length and time scales on which those voltages decay in response to a stimulus.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] Referring to the circuit diagram on the right, these scales can be determined from the resistances and capacitances per unit length.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] These time and length-scales can be used to understand the dependence of the conduction velocity on the diameter of the neuron in unmyelinated fibers.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] For example, the time-scale τ increases with both the membrane resistance *rm* and capacitance *cm*.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] As the capacitance increases, more charge must be transferred to produce a given transmembrane voltage (by the equation *Q* = *CV*); as the resistance increases, less charge is transferred per unit time, making the equilibration slower.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] In a similar manner, if the internal resistance per unit length *ri* is lower in one axon than in another (e.g., because the radius of the former is larger), the spatial decay length λ becomes longer and the conduction velocity of an action potential should increase.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p01] If the transmembrane resistance *rm* is increased, that lowers the average "leakage" current across the membrane, likewise causing *λ* to become longer, increasing the conduction velocity.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] In general, action potentials that reach the synaptic knobs cause a neurotransmitter to be released into the synaptic cleft.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Neurotransmitters are small molecules that may open ion channels in the postsynaptic cell; most axons have the same neurotransmitter at all of their termini.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] The arrival of the action potential opens voltage-sensitive calcium channels in the presynaptic membrane; the influx of calcium causes vesicles filled with neurotransmitter to migrate to the cell's surface and release their contents into the synaptic cleft.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] This complex process is inhibited by the neurotoxins tetanospasmin and botulinum toxin, which are responsible for tetanus and botulism, respectively.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Some synapses dispense with the "middleman" of the neurotransmitter, and connect the presynaptic and postsynaptic cells together.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] When an action potential reaches such a synapse, the ionic currents flowing into the presynaptic cell can cross the barrier of the two cell membranes and enter the postsynaptic cell through pores known as connexons.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Thus, the ionic currents of the presynaptic action potential can directly stimulate the postsynaptic cell.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Electrical synapses allow for faster transmission because they do not require the slow diffusion of neurotransmitters across the synaptic cleft.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Hence, electrical synapses are used whenever fast response and coordination of timing are crucial, as in escape reflexes, the retina of vertebrates, and the heart.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] A special case of a chemical synapse is the neuromuscular junction, in which the axon of a motor neuron terminates on a muscle fiber.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] In such cases, the released neurotransmitter is acetylcholine, which binds to the acetylcholine receptor, an integral membrane protein in the membrane (the *sarcolemma*) of the muscle fiber.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] However, the acetylcholine does not remain bound; rather, it dissociates and is hydrolyzed by the enzyme, acetylcholinesterase, located in the synapse.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] This enzyme quickly reduces the stimulus to the muscle, which allows the degree and timing of muscular contraction to be regulated delicately.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Some poisons inactivate acetylcholinesterase to prevent this control, such as the nerve agents sarin and tabun, and the insecticides diazinon and malathion.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] The cardiac action potential differs from the neuronal action potential by having an extended plateau, in which the membrane is held at a high voltage for a few hundred milliseconds prior to being repolarized by the potassium current as usual.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] This plateau is due to the action of slower calcium channels opening and holding the membrane voltage near their equilibrium potential even after the sodium channels have inactivated.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] The cardiac action potential plays an important role in coordinating the contraction of the heart.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] The cardiac cells of the sinoatrial node provide the pacemaker potential that synchronizes the heart.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] The action potentials of those cells propagate to and through the atrioventricular node (AV node), which is normally the only conduction pathway between the atria and the ventricles.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Action potentials from the AV node travel through the bundle of His and thence to the Purkinje fibers.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Conversely, anomalies in the cardiac action potential—whether due to a congenital mutation or injury—can lead to human pathologies, especially arrhythmias.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Several anti-arrhythmia drugs act on the cardiac action potential, such as quinidine, lidocaine, beta blockers, and verapamil.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] The action potential in a normal skeletal muscle cell is similar to the action potential in neurons.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Action potentials result from the depolarization of the cell membrane (the sarcolemma), which opens voltage-sensitive sodium channels; these become inactivated and the membrane is repolarized through the outward current of potassium ions.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] The resting potential prior to the action potential is typically −90mV, somewhat more negative than typical neurons.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] The muscle action potential lasts roughly 2–4 ms, the absolute refractory period is roughly 1–3 ms, and the conduction velocity along the muscle is roughly 5 m/s.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] The action potential releases calcium ions that free up the tropomyosin and allow the muscle to contract.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Muscle action potentials are provoked by the arrival of a pre-synaptic neuronal action potential at the neuromuscular junction, which is a common target for neurotoxins.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Plant and fungal cells are also electrically excitable.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] The fundamental difference from animal action potentials is that the depolarization in plant cells is not accomplished by an uptake of positive sodium ions, but by release of negative *chloride* ions.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Bose published the first measurements of action potentials in plants, which had previously been discovered by Burdon-Sanderson and Darwin.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] An increase in cytoplasmic calcium ions may be the cause of anion release into the cell.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] This makes calcium a precursor to ion movements, such as the influx of negative chloride ions and efflux of positive potassium ions, as seen in barley leaves.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] The initial influx of calcium ions also poses a small cellular depolarization, causing the voltage-gated ion channels to open and allowing full depolarization to be propagated by chloride ions.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] *Dionaea muscipula*) use sodium-gated channels to operate plant movements and "count" stimulation events to determine if a threshold for movement is met.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] *Dionaea muscipula*, also known as the Venus flytrap, is found in subtropical wetlands in North and South Carolina.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] When there are poor soil nutrients, the flytrap relies on a diet of insects and animals.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Despite research on the plant, there lacks an understanding behind the molecular basis to the Venus flytraps, and carnivore plants in general.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] However, plenty of research has been done on action potentials and how they affect movement and clockwork within the Venus flytrap.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] To start, the resting membrane potential of the Venus flytrap (−120 mV) is lower than animal cells (usually −90 mV to −40 mV).
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] The lower resting potential makes it easier to activate an action potential.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Thus, when an insect lands on the trap of the plant, it triggers a hair-like mechanoreceptor.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] This receptor then activates an action potential that lasts around 1.5 ms.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] This causes an increase of positive calcium ions into the cell, slightly depolarizing it.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] However, the flytrap does not close after one trigger.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Instead, it requires the activation of two or more hairs.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] If only one hair is triggered, it disregards the activation as a false positive.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Further, the second hair must be activated within a certain time interval (0.75–40 s) for it to register with the first activation.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Thus, a buildup of calcium begins and then slowly falls after the first trigger.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] When the second action potential is fired within the time interval, it reaches the calcium threshold to depolarize the cell, closing the trap on the prey within a fraction of a second.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Together with the subsequent release of positive potassium ions the action potential in plants involves an osmotic loss of salt (KCl).
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Whereas, the animal action potential is osmotically neutral because equal amounts of entering sodium and leaving potassium cancel each other osmotically.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] The interaction of electrical and osmotic relations in plant cells appears to have arisen from an osmotic function of electrical excitability in a common unicellular ancestors of plants and animals under changing salinity conditions.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Further, the present function of rapid signal transmission is seen as a newer accomplishment of metazoan cells in a more stable osmotic environment.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] It is likely that the familiar signaling function of action potentials in some vascular plants (e.g.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] *Mimosa pudica*) arose independently from that in metazoan excitable cells.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Unlike the rising phase and peak, the falling phase and after-hyperpolarization seem to depend primarily on cations that are not calcium.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] To initiate repolarization, the cell requires movement of potassium out of the cell through passive transportation on the membrane.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] This differs from neurons because the movement of potassium does not dominate the decrease in membrane potential.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] To fully repolarize, a plant cell requires energy in the form of ATP to assist in the release of hydrogen from the cell – utilizing a transporter called proton ATPase.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Action potentials are found throughout multicellular organisms, including plants, invertebrates such as insects, and vertebrates such as reptiles and mammals.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Sponges seem to be the main phylum of multicellular eukaryotes that does not transmit action potentials, although some studies have suggested that these organisms have a form of electrical signaling, too.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] The resting potential, as well as the size and duration of the action potential, have not varied much with evolution, although the conduction velocity does vary dramatically with axonal diameter and myelination.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Given its conservation throughout evolution, the action potential seems to confer evolutionary advantages.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] One function of action potentials is rapid, long-range signaling within the organism; the conduction velocity can exceed 110 m/s, which is one-third the speed of sound.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] For comparison, a hormone molecule carried in the bloodstream moves at roughly 8 m/s in large arteries.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Part of this function is the tight coordination of mechanical events, such as the contraction of the heart.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] A second function is the computation associated with its generation.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Being an all-or-none signal that does not decay with transmission distance, the action potential has similar advantages to digital electronics.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] The integration of various dendritic signals at the axon hillock and its thresholding to form a complex train of action potentials is another form of computation, one that has been exploited biologically to form central pattern generators and mimicked in artificial neural networks.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] The common prokaryotic/eukaryotic ancestor, which lived perhaps four billion years ago, is believed to have had voltage-gated channels.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] This functionality was likely, at some later point, cross-purposed to provide a communication mechanism.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Even modern single-celled bacteria can utilize action potentials to communicate with other bacteria in the same biofilm.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] The study of action potentials has required the development of new experimental methods.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] The initial work, prior to 1955, was carried out primarily by Alan Lloyd Hodgkin and Andrew Fielding Huxley, who were, along John Carew Eccles, awarded the 1963 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for their contribution to the description of the ionic basis of nerve conduction.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] It focused on three goals: isolating signals from single neurons or axons, developing fast, sensitive electronics, and shrinking electrodes enough that the voltage inside a single cell could be recorded.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] The first problem was solved by studying the giant axons found in the neurons of the squid (*Loligo forbesii* and *Doryteuthis pealeii*, at the time classified as *Loligo pealeii*).
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] These axons are so large in diameter (roughly 1 mm, or 100-fold larger than a typical neuron) that they can be seen with the naked eye, making them easy to extract and manipulate.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] However, they are not representative of all excitable cells, and numerous other systems with action potentials have been studied.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Since the current equals *C* times the rate of change of the transmembrane voltage *Vm*, the solution was to design a circuit that kept *Vm* fixed (zero rate of change) regardless of the currents flowing across the membrane.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Thus, the current required to keep *Vm* at a fixed value is a direct reflection of the current flowing through the membrane.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Other electronic advances included the use of Faraday cages and electronics with high input impedance, so that the measurement itself did not affect the voltage being measured.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] The third problem, that of obtaining electrodes small enough to record voltages within a single axon without perturbing it, was solved in 1949 with the invention of the glass micropipette electrode, which was quickly adopted by other researchers.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Refinements of this method are able to produce electrode tips that are as fine as 100 Å (10 nm), which also confers high input impedance.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Action potentials may also be recorded with small metal electrodes placed just next to a neuron, with neurochips containing EOSFETs, or optically with dyes that are sensitive to Ca2+ or to voltage.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] While glass micropipette electrodes measure the sum of the currents passing through many ion channels, studying the electrical properties of a single ion channel became possible in the 1970s with the development of the patch clamp by Erwin Neher and Bert Sakmann.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] For this discovery, they were awarded the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1991.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Patch-clamping verified that ionic channels have discrete states of conductance, such as open, closed and inactivated.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Optical imaging technologies have been developed in recent years to measure action potentials, either via simultaneous multisite recordings or with ultra-spatial resolution.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Using voltage-sensitive dyes, action potentials have been optically recorded from a tiny patch of cardiomyocyte membrane.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Several neurotoxins, both natural and synthetic, function by blocking the action potential.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Tetrodotoxin from the pufferfish and saxitoxin from the *Gonyaulax* (the dinoflagellate genus responsible for "red tides") block action potentials by inhibiting the voltage-sensitive sodium channel; similarly, dendrotoxin from the black mamba snake inhibits the voltage-sensitive potassium channel.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Such inhibitors of ion channels serve an important research purpose, by allowing scientists to "turn off" specific channels at will, thus isolating the other channels' contributions; they can also be useful in purifying ion channels by affinity chromatography or in assaying their concentration.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] However, such inhibitors also make effective neurotoxins, and have been considered for use as chemical weapons.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Neurotoxins aimed at the ion channels of insects have been effective insecticides; one example is the synthetic permethrin, which prolongs the activation of the sodium channels involved in action potentials.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] The ion channels of insects are sufficiently different from their human counterparts that there are few side effects in humans.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] The role of electricity in the nervous systems of animals was first observed in dissected frogs by Luigi Galvani, who studied it from 1791 to 1797.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Galvani's results inspired Alessandro Volta to develop the Voltaic pile—the earliest-known electric battery—with which he studied animal electricity (such as electric eels) and the physiological responses to applied direct-current voltages.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] In the 19th century scientists studied the propagation of electrical signals in whole nerves (i.e., bundles of neurons) and demonstrated that nervous tissue was made up of cells, instead of an interconnected network of tubes (a *reticulum*).
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Carlo Matteucci followed up Galvani's studies and demonstrated that injured nerves and muscles in frogs could produce direct current.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Matteucci's work inspired the German physiologist, Emil du Bois-Reymond, who discovered in 1843 that stimulating these muscle and nerve preparations produced a notable diminution in their resting currents, making him the first researcher to identify the electrical nature of the action potential.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] The conduction velocity of action potentials was then measured in 1850 by du Bois-Reymond's friend, Hermann von Helmholtz.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Progress in electrophysiology stagnated thereafter due to the limitations of chemical theory and experimental practice.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] To establish that nervous tissue is made up of discrete cells, the Spanish physician Santiago Ramón y Cajal and his students used a stain developed by Camillo Golgi to reveal the myriad shapes of neurons, which they rendered painstakingly.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] For their discoveries, Golgi and Ramón y Cajal were awarded the 1906 Nobel Prize in Physiology.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Their work resolved a long-standing controversy in the neuroanatomy of the 19th century; Golgi himself had argued for the network model of the nervous system.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] The 20th century saw significant breakthroughs in electrophysiology.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] In 1902 and again in 1912, Julius Bernstein advanced the hypothesis that the action potential resulted from a change in the permeability of the axonal membrane to ions.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Bernstein's hypothesis was confirmed by Ken Cole and Howard Curtis, who showed that membrane conductance increases during an action potential.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] In 1907, Louis Lapicque suggested that the action potential was generated as a threshold was crossed, what would be later shown as a product of the dynamical systems of ionic conductances.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] In 1949, Alan Hodgkin and Bernard Katz refined Bernstein's hypothesis by considering that the axonal membrane might have different permeabilities to different ions; in particular, they demonstrated the crucial role of the sodium permeability for the action potential.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] They made the first actual recording of the electrical changes across the neuronal membrane that mediate the action potential.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Hodgkin and Huxley correlated the properties of their mathematical model with discrete ion channels that could exist in several different states, including "open", "closed", and "inactivated".
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Their hypotheses were confirmed in the mid-1970s and 1980s by Erwin Neher and Bert Sakmann, who developed the technique of patch clamping to examine the conductance states of individual ion channels.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] In the 21st century, researchers are beginning to understand the structural basis for these conductance states and for the selectivity of channels for their species of ion, through the atomic-resolution crystal structures, fluorescence distance measurements and cryo-electron microscopy studies.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Julius Bernstein was also the first to introduce the Nernst equation for resting potential across the membrane; this was generalized by David E.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Goldman to the eponymous Goldman equation in 1943.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] The sodium–potassium pump was identified in 1957 and its properties gradually elucidated, culminating in the determination of its atomic-resolution structure by X-ray crystallography.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] The crystal structures of related ionic pumps have also been solved, giving a broader view of how these molecular machines work.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] Mathematical and computational models are essential for understanding the action potential, and offer predictions that may be tested against experimental data, providing a stringent test of a theory.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] The most important and accurate of the early neural models is the Hodgkin–Huxley model, which describes the action potential by a coupled set of four ordinary differential equations (ODEs).
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] The properties of the Hodgkin–Huxley and FitzHugh–Nagumo models and their relatives, such as the Bonhoeffer–Van der Pol model, have been well-studied within mathematics, computation and electronics.
[src:action-potential/action-potential-p02] However the simple models of generator potential and action potential fail to accurately reproduce the near threshold neural spike rate and spike shape, specifically for the mechanoreceptors like the Pacinian corpuscle.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] In biology, **depolarization** or **hypopolarization** is a change within a cell, during which the cell undergoes a shift in electric charge distribution, resulting in less negative charge inside the cell compared to the outside.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] Depolarization is essential to the function of many cells, communication between cells, and the overall physiology of an organism.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] It is especially important to electrical signaling in neurons and muscle cells.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] It also affects many non-excitable cells by changing calcium regulation or gene expression.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] Most cells in higher organisms maintain an internal environment that is negatively charged relative to the cell's exterior.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] This difference in charge is called the cell's membrane potential.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] In the process of depolarization, the negative internal charge of the cell temporarily becomes more positive (less negative).
[src:action-potential/depolarization] This shift from a negative to a more positive membrane potential occurs during several processes, including an action potential.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] During an action potential, the depolarization is so large that the potential difference across the cell membrane briefly reverses polarity, with the inside of the cell becoming positively charged.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] The change in charge typically occurs due to an influx of sodium ions into a cell, although it can be mediated by an influx of any kind of cation or efflux of any kind of anion.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] The opposite of a depolarization is called a hyperpolarization.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] Usage of the term "depolarization" in biology differs from its use in physics, where it refers to situations in which any form of electrical polarity ( *i.e.* the presence of any electrical charge, whether positive or negative) changes to a value of zero.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] Depolarization is sometimes referred to as "hypopolarization" (as opposed to hyp**er**polarization).
[src:action-potential/depolarization] The process of depolarization is entirely dependent upon the intrinsic electrical nature of most cells.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] When a cell is at rest, the cell maintains what is known as a resting potential.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] The resting potential generated by nearly all cells results in the interior of the cell having a negative charge compared to the exterior of the cell.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] To maintain this electrical imbalance, ions are transported across the cell's plasma membrane.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] The resting potential must be established within a cell before the cell can be depolarized.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] There are many mechanisms by which a cell can establish a resting potential, however there is a typical pattern of generating this resting potential that many cells follow.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] The generation of a negative resting potential within the cell involves the utilization of ion channels, ion pumps, and voltage-gated ion channels by the cell.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] However, the process of generating the resting potential within the cell also creates an environment outside the cell that favors depolarization.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] The sodium potassium pump is largely responsible for the optimization of conditions on both the interior and the exterior of the cell for depolarization.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] This pump is an ATPase that pumps three sodium ions out of the cell and two potassium ions into the cell with every ATP consumed.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] While there is an excessive amount of potassium in the cell and sodium outside the cell, the generated resting potential maintains the closure of voltage-gated ion channels in the plasma membrane.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] This not only prevents the diffusion of ions pumped across the membrane but also involves the activity of potassium leak channels, allowing a controlled passive efflux of potassium ions, which contributes to the establishment of the negative resting potential.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] Additionally, despite the high concentration of positively-charged potassium ions, most cells contain internal components (of negative charge), which accumulate to establish a negative inner charge.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] After a cell has established a resting potential, that cell has the capacity to undergo depolarization.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] Depolarization is the process by which the membrane potential becomes less negative, facilitating the generation of an action potential.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] For this rapid change to take place within the interior of the cell, several events must occur along the plasma membrane of the cell.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] While the sodium–potassium pump continues to work, the voltage-gated sodium and calcium channels that had been closed while the cell was at resting potential are opened in response to an initial change in voltage.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] As a change in the neuronal charge leads to the opening of voltage-gated sodium channels, this results in an influx of sodium ions down their electrochemical gradient.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] Sodium ions enter the cell, and they contribute a positive charge to the cell interior, causing a change in the membrane potential from negative to positive.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] The initial sodium ion influx triggers the opening of additional sodium channels (positive-feedback loop), leading to further sodium ion transfer into the cell and sustaining the depolarization process until the positive equilibrium potential is reached.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] Sodium channels possess an inherent inactivation mechanism that prompts rapid reclosure, even as the membrane remains depolarized.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] During this equilibrium, the sodium channels enter an inactivated state, temporarily halting the influx of sodium ions until the membrane potential becomes negatively charged again.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] Once the cell's interior is sufficiently positively charged, depolarization concludes, and the channels close once more.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] After a cell has been depolarized, it undergoes one final change in internal charge.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] Following depolarization, the voltage-gated sodium ion channels that had been open while the cell was undergoing depolarization close again.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] The increased positive charge within the cell now causes the potassium channels to open.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] Potassium ions (K+) begin to move down the electrochemical gradient (in favor of the concentration gradient and the newly established electrical gradient).
[src:action-potential/depolarization] As potassium moves out of the cell the potential within the cell decreases and approaches its resting potential once more.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] The sodium potassium pump works continuously throughout this process.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] The process of repolarization causes an overshoot in the potential of the cell.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] Potassium ions continue to move out of the axon so much that the resting potential is exceeded and the new cell potential becomes more negative than the resting potential.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] The resting potential is ultimately re-established by the closing of all voltage-gated ion channels and the activity of the sodium potassium ion pump.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] Depolarization is essential to the functions of many cells in the human body, which is exemplified by the transmission of stimuli both within a neuron and between two neurons.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] The reception of stimuli, neural integration of those stimuli, and the neuron's response to stimuli all rely upon the ability of neurons to utilize depolarization to transmit stimuli either within a neuron or between neurons.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] Stimuli to neurons can be physical, electrical, or chemical, and can either inhibit or excite the neuron being stimulated.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] An inhibitory stimulus is transmitted to the dendrite of a neuron, causing hyperpolarization of the neuron.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] The hyperpolarization following an inhibitory stimulus causes a further decrease in voltage within the neuron below the resting potential.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] By hyperpolarizing a neuron, an inhibitory stimulus results in a greater negative charge that must be overcome for depolarization to occur.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] Excitation stimuli, on the other hand, increase the voltage in the neuron, which leads to a neuron that is easier to depolarize than the same neuron in the resting state.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] Regardless of it being excitatory or inhibitory, the stimulus travels down the dendrites of a neuron to the cell body for integration.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] Once the stimuli have reached the cell body, the nerve must integrate the various stimuli before the nerve can respond.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] The stimuli that have traveled down the dendrites converge at the axon hillock, where they are summed to determine the neuronal response.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] If the sum of the stimuli reaches a certain voltage, known as the threshold potential, depolarization continues from the axon hillock down the axon.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] The surge of depolarization traveling from the axon hillock to the axon terminal is known as an action potential.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] Action potentials reach the axon terminal, where the action potential triggers the release of neurotransmitters from the neuron.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] The neurotransmitters that are released from the axon continue on to stimulate other cells such as other neurons or muscle cells.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] After an action potential travels down the axon of a neuron, the resting membrane potential of the axon must be restored before another action potential can travel the axon.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] This is known as the recovery period of the neuron, during which the neuron cannot transmit another action potential.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] The importance and versatility of depolarization within cells can be seen in the relationship between rod cells in the eye and their associated neurons.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] When rod cells are in the dark, they are depolarized.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] In the rod cells, this depolarization is maintained by ion channels that remain open due to the higher voltage of the rod cell in the depolarized state.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] The ion channels allow calcium and sodium to pass freely into the cell, maintaining the depolarized state.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] Rod cells in the depolarized state constantly release neurotransmitters which in turn stimulate the nerves associated with rod cells.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] This cycle is broken when rod cells are exposed to light; the absorption of light by the rod cell causes the channels that had facilitated the entry of sodium and calcium into the rod cell to close.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] When these channels close, the rod cells produce fewer neurotransmitters, which is perceived by the brain as an increase in light.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] Therefore, in the case of rod cells and their associated neurons, depolarization actually prevents a signal from reaching the brain as opposed to stimulating the transmission of the signal.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] Depolarization occurs in the four chambers of the heart: both atria first, and then both ventricles.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] The SA node sends the depolarization wave to the atrioventricular (AV) node which—with about a 100 ms delay to let the atria finish contracting—then causes contraction in both ventricles, seen in the QRS wave.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] At the same time, the atria re-polarize and relax.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] The ventricles are re-polarized and relaxed at the T wave.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] This process continues regularly, unless there is a problem in the heart.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] There are drugs, called depolarization blocking agents, that cause prolonged depolarization by opening channels responsible for depolarization and not allowing them to close, preventing repolarization.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] Examples include the nicotinic agonists, suxamethonium and decamethonium.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] Succinylcholine (suxamethonium) activates nicotinic acetylcholine receptors and keeps the endplate depolarized.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] It functionally blocks transmission because voltage-gated sodium channels remain inactivated.
[src:action-potential/depolarization] Decamethonium is an older depolarizing blocker with a similar principle and of interest for many researchers.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] The **Hodgkin–Huxley model**, or **conductance-based model**, is a mathematical model that describes how action potentials in neurons are initiated and propagated.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] It is a set of nonlinear differential equations that approximates the electrical engineering characteristics of excitable cells such as neurons and muscle cells.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] It is a continuous-time dynamical system.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] Alan Hodgkin and Andrew Huxley described the model in 1952 to explain the ionic mechanisms underlying the initiation and propagation of action potentials in the squid giant axon.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] They received the 1963 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for this work.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] The typical Hodgkin–Huxley model treats each component of an excitable cell as an electrical element (as shown in the figure).
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] The lipid bilayer is represented as a capacitance (Cm).
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] Voltage-gated ion channels are represented by electrical conductances (*g**n*, where *n* is the specific ion channel) that depend on both voltage and time.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] Leak channels are represented by linear conductances (*g**L*).
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] The electrochemical gradients driving the flow of ions are represented by voltage sources (*E**n*) whose voltages are determined by the ratio of the intra- and extracellular concentrations of the ionic species of interest.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] Finally, ion pumps are represented by current sources (*I**p*).
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] The membrane potential is denoted by *Vm*.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] where $V_{i}$ is the reversal potential of the specific ion channel.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] The time dependent elements of this equation are *V**m*, *g**Na*, and *g**K*, where the last two conductances depend explicitly on the membrane voltage (*V**m*) as well.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] In voltage-gated ion channels, the channel conductance is a function of both time and voltage ( $g_{n}(t,V)$ in the figure), while in leak channels, $g_{l}$ , it is a constant ( $g_{L}$ in the figure).
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] The current generated by ion pumps is dependent on the ionic species specific to that pump.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] The following sections will describe these formulations in more detail.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] Using a series of voltage clamp experiments and by varying extracellular sodium and potassium concentrations, Hodgkin and Huxley developed a model in which the properties of an excitable cell are described by a set of four ordinary differential equations.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] where *I* is the current per unit area and $\alpha _{i}$ and $\beta _{i}$ are rate constants for the *i*-th ion channel, which depend on voltage but not time. ${\bar {g}}_{n}$ is the maximal value of the conductance.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] *n*, *m*, and *h* are dimensionless probabilities between 0 and 1 that are associated with potassium channel subunit activation, sodium channel subunit activation, and sodium channel subunit inactivation, respectively.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] For instance, given that potassium channels in squid giant axon are made up of four subunits which all need to be in the open state for the channel to allow the passage of potassium ions, the *n* needs to be raised to the fourth power.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] $p_{\infty }$ and $(1-p_{\infty })$ are the steady state values for activation and inactivation, respectively, and are usually represented by Boltzmann equations as functions of $V_{m}$ .
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] where $V=V_{rest}-V_{m}$ denotes the negative depolarization in mV.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] In order to characterize voltage-gated channels, the equations can be fitted to voltage clamp data.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] For a derivation of the Hodgkin–Huxley equations under voltage-clamp, see.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] In order to arrive at the complete solution for a propagated action potential, one must write the current term *I* on the left-hand side of the first differential equation in terms of *V*, so that the equation becomes an equation for voltage alone.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] where *a* is the radius of the axon, *R* is the specific resistance of the axoplasm, and *x* is the position along the nerve fiber.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] Substitution of this expression for *I* transforms the original set of equations into a set of partial differential equations, because the voltage becomes a function of both *x* and *t*.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] The Levenberg–Marquardt algorithm is often used to fit these equations to voltage-clamp data.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] While the original experiments involved only sodium and potassium channels, the Hodgkin–Huxley model can also be extended to account for other species of ion channels.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] Leak channels account for the natural permeability of the membrane to ions and take the form of the equation for voltage-gated channels, where the conductance $g_{leak}$ is a constant.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] Thus, the leak current due to passive leak ion channels in the Hodgkin-Huxley formalism is $I_{l}=g_{leak}(V-V_{leak})$ .
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] The membrane potential depends upon the maintenance of ionic concentration gradients across it.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] The maintenance of these concentration gradients requires active transport of ionic species.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] The sodium-potassium and sodium-calcium exchangers are the best known of these.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] Some of the basic properties of the Na/Ca exchanger have already been well-established: the stoichiometry of exchange is 3 Na+: 1 Ca2+ and the exchanger is electrogenic and voltage-sensitive.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] The Na/K exchanger has also been described in detail, with a 3 Na+: 2 K+ stoichiometry.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] The Hodgkin–Huxley model can be thought of as a differential equation system with four state variables, $V_{m}(t),n(t),m(t)$ , and $h(t)$ , that change with respect to time t .
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] The system is difficult to study because it is a nonlinear system, cannot be solved analytically, and therefore has no closed-form solution.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] However, there are many numerical methods available to analyze the system.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] Certain properties and general behaviors, such as limit cycles, can be proven to exist.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] Because there are four state variables, visualizing the path in phase space can be difficult.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] Usually two variables are chosen, voltage $V_{m}(t)$ and the potassium gating variable $n(t)$ , allowing one to visualize the limit cycle.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] However, one must be careful because this is an ad-hoc method of visualizing the 4-dimensional system.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] This does not prove the existence of the limit cycle.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] A better projection can be constructed from a careful analysis of the Jacobian of the system, evaluated at the equilibrium point.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] Specifically, the eigenvalues of the Jacobian are indicative of the center manifold's existence.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] Likewise, the eigenvectors of the Jacobian reveal the center manifold's orientation.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] The Hodgkin–Huxley model has two negative eigenvalues and two complex eigenvalues with slightly positive real parts.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] The eigenvectors associated with the two negative eigenvalues will reduce to zero as time *t* increases.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] The remaining two complex eigenvectors define the center manifold.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] In other words, the 4-dimensional system collapses onto a 2-dimensional plane.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] Any solution starting off the center manifold will decay towards the center manifold.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] Furthermore, the limit cycle is contained on the center manifold.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] If the injected current I were used as a bifurcation parameter, then the Hodgkin–Huxley model undergoes a Hopf bifurcation.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] As with most neuronal models, increasing the injected current will increase the firing rate of the neuron.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] One consequence of the Hopf bifurcation is that there is a minimum firing rate.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] This means that either the neuron is not firing at all (corresponding to zero frequency), or firing at the minimum firing rate.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] Because of the all-or-none principle, there is no smooth increase in action potential amplitude, but rather there is a sudden "jump" in amplitude.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] The resulting transition is known as a canard.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] The Hodgkin–Huxley model is regarded as one of the great achievements of 20th-century biophysics.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] Several simplified neuronal models have also been developed (such as the FitzHugh–Nagumo model), facilitating efficient large-scale simulation of groups of neurons, as well as mathematical insight into dynamics of action potential generation.
[src:action-potential/hodgkin-huxley-model] Ion-channel parameters derived from Hodgkin–Huxley-type models fitted to single-cell electrophysiological data have been shown to correlate with single-cell transcriptomic profiles across neuronal cell types, underscoring the biological realism of such models.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] By convention it is written as Vm=Vinside−Voutside, so a negative membrane potential means the cell interior is negative relative to the outside.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Essentially, It equals the interior potential minus the exterior potential.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] This is the energy per charge which is required to move a very small positive charge at constant velocity across the cell membrane from the exterior to the interior.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Note, though, that if the charge is allowed to change velocity, the change of kinetic energy and production of radiation must be taken into account.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Typical values of membrane potential is normally given in units of millivolts and denoted as mV.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] In many animal cells, Vm is typically in the order of tens of millivolts.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] It commonly falls in the range of about −20 mV to −200 mV depending on the cell type and state.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] For such typical negative membrane potentials, positive work is required to move a positive charge from the interior to the exterior.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] However, thermal kinetic energy allows ions to overcome the potential difference.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] For a selectively permeable membrane, this permits a net flow against the gradient.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Although the entire cell is considered negative inside, the fluids in the cell are electrically neutral.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The presence of the voltage is due to the thin layer of charge that accumulates at the surfaces of the cell membrane.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The cell membrane is only a few nanometers thick, and as such, even a voltage of 100 mV across this thickness generates an electric field that is extremely strong on the cell membrane.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] All animal cells are surrounded by a membrane composed of a lipid bilayer with proteins embedded in it.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The membrane serves both as a capacitor and as a diffusion barrier to the movement of ions.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Ion pumps actively push ions across the membrane and establish concentration gradients across the membrane, and ion channels allow ions to move across the membrane down their electrochemical gradients.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Ion channels and ion pumps are transmembrane proteins, and are electrically analogous to resistors and current sources (batteries), and contribute to the voltage across the two sides of the membrane.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] All plasma membranes have an electrical potential across them, with the inside usually negative with respect to the outside.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The membrane potential has two basic functions.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] First, it allows a cell to function as a battery, providing power to operate a variety of "molecular devices" embedded in the membrane.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Second, in electrically **excitable cells** such as neurons and muscle cells, it is used for transmitting signals between different parts of a cell.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Signals are generated in excitable cells by opening or closing of ion channels at one point in the membrane, producing a local change in the membrane potential.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] This change in the electric field can be quickly sensed by either adjacent or more distant ion channels in the membrane.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Those ion channels can then open or close as a result of the potential change, reproducing the signal.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] In non-excitable cells, and in excitable cells in their baseline states, the membrane potential is held at a relatively stable value, called the resting potential.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] For neurons, resting potential is defined as ranging from −80 to −70 millivolts; that is, the interior of a cell has a negative baseline voltage of a bit less than one-tenth of a volt.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The opening and closing of ion channels can induce a departure from the resting potential.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] This is called a depolarization if the interior voltage becomes less negative (say from −70 mV to −60 mV), or a hyperpolarization if the interior voltage becomes more negative (say from −70 mV to −80 mV).
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] In excitable cells, a sufficiently large depolarization can evoke an action potential, in which the membrane potential changes rapidly and significantly for a short time (on the order of 1 to 100 milliseconds), often reversing its polarity.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Action potentials are generated by the activation of certain voltage-gated ion channels.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] In neurons, the factors that influence the membrane potential are diverse.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] They include numerous types of ion channels, some of which are chemically gated and some of which are voltage-gated.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Because voltage-gated ion channels are controlled by the membrane potential, while the membrane potential itself is influenced by these same ion channels, feedback loops that allow for complex temporal dynamics arise, including oscillations and regenerative events such as action potentials.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Differences in the concentrations of ions on opposite sides of a cellular membrane lead to a voltage called the **membrane potential**.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Many ions have a concentration gradient across the membrane, including potassium (K+), which is at a high concentration inside and a low concentration outside the membrane.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Sodium (Na+) and chloride (Cl−) ions are at high concentrations in the extracellular region, and low concentrations in the intracellular regions.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] These concentration gradients provide the potential energy to drive the formation of the membrane potential.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] This voltage is established when the membrane has permeability to one or more ions.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] In the simplest case, illustrated in the top diagram ("Ion concentration gradients"), if the membrane is selectively permeable to potassium, these positively charged ions can diffuse down the concentration gradient to the outside of the cell, leaving behind uncompensated negative charges.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] This separation of charges is what causes the membrane potential.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The system as a whole is electro-neutral.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The uncompensated positive charges outside the cell, and the uncompensated negative charges inside the cell, physically line up on the membrane surface and attract each other across the lipid bilayer.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Thus, the membrane potential is physically located only in the immediate vicinity of the membrane.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] It is the separation of these charges across the membrane that is the basis of the membrane voltage.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The top diagram is only an approximation of the ionic contributions to the membrane potential.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Other ions including sodium, chloride, calcium, and others play a more minor role, even though they have strong concentration gradients, because they have more limited permeability than potassium.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The membrane potential in a cell derives ultimately from two factors: electrical force and diffusion.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Electrical force arises from the mutual attraction between particles with opposite electrical charges (positive and negative) and the mutual repulsion between particles with the same type of charge (both positive or both negative).
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Diffusion arises from the statistical tendency of particles to redistribute from regions where they are highly concentrated to regions where the concentration is low.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Voltage, which is synonymous with *difference in electrical potential*, is the ability to drive an electric current across a resistance.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Indeed, the simplest definition of a voltage is given by Ohm's law: V=IR, where V is voltage, I is current and R is resistance.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] If a voltage source such as a battery is placed in an electrical circuit, the higher the voltage of the source the greater the amount of current that it will drive across the available resistance.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The functional significance of voltage lies only in potential *differences* between two points in a circuit.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The idea of a voltage at a single point is meaningless.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] It is conventional in electronics to assign a voltage of zero to some arbitrarily chosen element of the circuit, and then assign voltages for other elements measured relative to that zero point.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] There is no significance in which element is chosen as the zero point—the function of a circuit depends only on the differences not on voltages *per se*.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] However, in most cases and by convention, the zero level is most often assigned to the portion of a circuit that is in contact with ground.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The same principle applies to voltage in cell biology.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] In electrically active tissue, the potential difference between any two points can be measured by inserting an electrode at each point, for example one inside and one outside the cell, and connecting both electrodes to the leads of what is in essence a specialized voltmeter.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] By convention, the zero potential value is assigned to the outside of the cell and the sign of the potential difference between the outside and the inside is determined by the potential of the inside relative to the outside zero.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] In mathematical terms, the definition of voltage begins with the concept of an electric field **E**, a vector field assigning a magnitude and direction to each point in space.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] In many situations, the electric field is a conservative field, which means that it can be expressed as the gradient of a scalar function *V*, that is, **E** = −∇*V*.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] This scalar field *V* is referred to as the voltage distribution.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The definition allows for an arbitrary constant of integration—this is why absolute values of voltage are not meaningful.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] In general, electric fields can be treated as conservative only if magnetic fields do not significantly influence them, but this condition usually applies well to biological tissue.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Because the electric field is the gradient of the voltage distribution, rapid changes in voltage within a small region imply a strong electric field; on the converse, if the voltage remains approximately the same over a large region, the electric fields in that region must be weak.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] A strong electric field, equivalent to a strong voltage gradient, implies that a strong force is exerted on any charged particles that lie within the region.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Electrical signals within biological organisms are, in general, driven by ions.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The most important cations for the action potential are sodium (Na+) and potassium (K+).
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Both of these are *monovalent* cations that carry a single positive charge.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Action potentials can also involve calcium (Ca2+), which is a *divalent* cation that carries a double positive charge.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The chloride anion (Cl−) plays a major role in the action potentials of some algae, but plays a negligible role in the action potentials of most animals.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Ions cross the cell membrane under two influences: diffusion and electric fields.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] A simple example wherein two solutions—A and B—are separated by a porous barrier illustrates that diffusion will ensure that they will eventually mix into equal solutions.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] This mixing occurs because of the difference in their concentrations.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The region with high concentration will diffuse out toward the region with low concentration.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] To extend the example, let solution A have 30 sodium ions and 30 chloride ions.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Also, let solution B have only 20 sodium ions and 20 chloride ions.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Assuming the barrier allows both types of ions to travel through it, then a steady state will be reached whereby both solutions have 25 sodium ions and 25 chloride ions.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] If, however, the porous barrier is selective to which ions are let through, then diffusion alone will not determine the resulting solution.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Returning to the previous example, let's now construct a barrier that is permeable only to sodium ions.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Now, only sodium is allowed to diffuse cross the barrier from its higher concentration in solution A to the lower concentration in solution B.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] This will result in a greater accumulation of sodium ions than chloride ions in solution B and a lesser number of sodium ions than chloride ions in solution A.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] This means that there is a net positive charge in solution B from the higher concentration of positively charged sodium ions than negatively charged chloride ions.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Likewise, there is a net negative charge in solution A from the greater concentration of negative chloride ions than positive sodium ions.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Since opposite charges attract and like charges repel, the ions are now also influenced by electrical fields as well as forces of diffusion.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Therefore, positive sodium ions will be less likely to travel to the now-more-positive B solution and remain in the now-more-negative A solution.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The point at which the forces of the electric fields completely counteract the force due to diffusion is called the equilibrium potential.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] At this point, the net flow of the specific ion (in this case sodium) is zero.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Every cell is enclosed in a plasma membrane, which has the structure of a lipid bilayer with many types of large molecules embedded in it.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Because it is made of lipid molecules, the plasma membrane intrinsically has a high electrical resistivity, in other words a low intrinsic permeability to ions.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] However, some of the molecules embedded in the membrane are capable either of actively transporting ions from one side of the membrane to the other or of providing channels through which they can move.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] In electrical terminology, the plasma membrane functions as a combined resistor and capacitor.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Resistance arises from the fact that the membrane impedes the movement of charges across it.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Capacitance arises from the fact that the lipid bilayer is so thin that an accumulation of charged particles on one side gives rise to an electrical force that pulls oppositely charged particles toward the other side.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The capacitance of the membrane is relatively unaffected by the molecules that are embedded in it, so it has a more or less invariant value estimated at 2 μF/cm2 (the total capacitance of a patch of membrane is proportional to its area).
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The conductance of a pure lipid bilayer is so low, on the other hand, that in biological situations it is always dominated by the conductance of alternative pathways provided by embedded molecules.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Thus, the capacitance of the membrane is more or less fixed, but the resistance is highly variable.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The thickness of a plasma membrane is estimated to be about 7–8 nanometers.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Because the membrane is so thin, it does not take a very large transmembrane voltage to create a strong electric field within it.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The resistance of a pure lipid bilayer to the passage of ions across it is very high, but structures embedded in the membrane can greatly enhance ion movement, either actively or passively.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] This is achieved via the mechanisms of active transport and facilitated diffusion.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The two types of structure that play the largest roles are ion channels and ion pumps, both usually formed from assemblages of protein molecules.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Ion channels provide passageways through which ions can move.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] In most cases, an ion channel is permeable only to specific types of ions (for example, sodium and potassium but not chloride or calcium), and sometimes the permeability varies depending on the direction of ion movement.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Ion pumps, also known as ion transporters or carrier proteins, actively transport specific types of ions from one side of the membrane to the other, sometimes using energy derived from metabolic processes to do so.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Ion pumps are integral membrane proteins that carry out active transport, i.e., use cellular energy (ATP) to "pump" the ions against their concentration gradient.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Such ion pumps take in ions from one side of the membrane (decreasing its concentration there) and release them on the other side (increasing its concentration there).
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The ion pump most relevant to the action potential is the sodium–potassium pump, which transports three sodium ions out of the cell and two potassium ions in.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] As a consequence, the concentration of potassium ions K+ inside the neuron is roughly 30-fold larger than the outside concentration, whereas the sodium concentration outside is roughly five-fold larger than inside.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] In a similar manner, other ions have different concentrations inside and outside the neuron, such as calcium, chloride and magnesium.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The sodium-potassium pump is relatively slow in operation.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] If a cell were initialized with equal concentrations of sodium and potassium everywhere, it would take hours for the pump to establish equilibrium.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The pump operates constantly, but becomes progressively less efficient as the concentrations of sodium and potassium available for pumping are reduced.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Ion pumps influence the action potential only by establishing the relative ratio of intracellular and extracellular ion concentrations.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The action potential involves mainly the opening and closing of ion channels not ion pumps.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] If the ion pumps are turned off by removing their energy source, or by adding an inhibitor such as ouabain, the axon can still fire hundreds of thousands of action potentials before their amplitudes begin to decay significantly.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] In particular, ion pumps play no significant role in the repolarization of the membrane after an action potential.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Another functionally important ion pump is the sodium-calcium exchanger.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] This pump operates in a conceptually similar way to the sodium-potassium pump, except that in each cycle it exchanges three Na+ from the extracellular space for one Ca++ from the intracellular space.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Because the net flow of charge is inward, this pump runs "downhill", in effect, and therefore does not require any energy source except the membrane voltage.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Its most important effect is to pump calcium outward—it also allows an inward flow of sodium, thereby counteracting the sodium-potassium pump, but, because overall sodium and potassium concentrations are much higher than calcium concentrations, this effect is relatively unimportant.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The net result of the sodium-calcium exchanger is that in the resting state, intracellular calcium concentrations become very low.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Ion channels are integral membrane proteins with a pore through which ions can travel between extracellular space and cell interior.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Most channels are specific (selective) for one ion; for example, most potassium channels are characterized by 1000:1 selectivity ratio for potassium over sodium, though potassium and sodium ions have the same charge and differ only slightly in their radius.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The channel pore is typically so small that ions must pass through it in single-file order.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Channel pores can be either open or closed for ion passage, although a number of channels demonstrate various sub-conductance levels.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] When a channel is open, ions permeate through the channel pore down the transmembrane concentration gradient for that particular ion.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Rate of ionic flow through the channel, i.e. single-channel current amplitude, is determined by the maximum channel conductance and electrochemical driving force for that ion, which is the difference between the instantaneous value of the membrane potential and the value of the reversal potential.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] A channel may have several different states (corresponding to different conformations of the protein), but each such state is either open or closed.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] In general, closed states correspond either to a contraction of the pore—making it impassable to the ion—or to a separate part of the protein, stoppering the pore.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] For example, the voltage-dependent sodium channel undergoes *inactivation*, in which a portion of the protein swings into the pore, sealing it.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] This inactivation shuts off the sodium current and plays a critical role in the action potential.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Ion channels can be classified by how they respond to their environment.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] For example, the ion channels involved in the action potential are *voltage-sensitive channels*; they open and close in response to the voltage across the membrane.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] *Ligand-gated channels* form another important class; these ion channels open and close in response to the binding of a ligand molecule, such as a neurotransmitter.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Other ion channels open and close with mechanical forces.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Still other ion channels—such as those of sensory neurons—open and close in response to other stimuli, such as light, temperature or pressure.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Leakage channels are the simplest type of ion channel, in that their permeability is more or less constant.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The types of leakage channels that have the greatest significance in neurons are potassium and chloride channels.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Ligand-gated ion channels are channels whose permeability is greatly increased when some type of chemical ligand binds to the protein structure.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Animal cells contain hundreds, if not thousands, of types of these.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] A large subset function as neurotransmitter receptors—they occur at postsynaptic sites, and the chemical ligand that gates them is released by the presynaptic axon terminal.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] One example of this type is the AMPA receptor, a receptor for the neurotransmitter glutamate that when activated allows passage of sodium and potassium ions.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Another example is the GABAA receptor, a receptor for the neurotransmitter GABA that when activated allows passage of chloride ions.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Neurotransmitter receptors are activated by ligands that appear in the extracellular area, but there are other types of ligand-gated channels that are controlled by interactions on the intracellular side.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Voltage-gated ion channels, also known as *voltage dependent ion channels*, are channels whose permeability is influenced by the membrane potential.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] They form another very large group, with each member having a particular ion selectivity and a particular voltage dependence.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Many are also time-dependent—in other words, they do not respond immediately to a voltage change but only after a delay.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The channel is closed at the resting voltage level, but opens abruptly when the voltage exceeds a certain threshold, allowing a large influx of sodium ions that produces a very rapid change in the membrane potential.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Recovery from an action potential is partly dependent on a type of voltage-gated potassium channel that is closed at the resting voltage level but opens as a consequence of the large voltage change produced during the action potential.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The reversal potential (or *equilibrium potential*) of an ion is the value of transmembrane voltage at which diffusive and electrical forces counterbalance, so that there is no net ion flow across the membrane.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] This means that the transmembrane voltage exactly opposes the force of diffusion of the ion, such that the net current of the ion across the membrane is zero and unchanging.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The reversal potential is important because it gives the voltage that acts on channels permeable to that ion—in other words, it gives the voltage that the ion concentration gradient generates when it acts as a battery.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The equilibrium potential of a particular ion is usually designated by the notation *E*ion.The equilibrium potential for any ion can be calculated using the Nernst equation.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Even if two different ions have the same charge (i.e., K+ and Na+), they can still have very different equilibrium potentials, provided their outside and/or inside concentrations differ.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Take, for example, the equilibrium potentials of potassium and sodium in neurons.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The potassium equilibrium potential *E*K is −84 mV with 5 mM potassium outside and 140 mM inside.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] On the other hand, the sodium equilibrium potential, *E*Na, is approximately +66 mV with approximately 12 mM sodium inside and 140 mM outside.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] A neuron's resting membrane potential actually changes during the development of an organism.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] In order for a neuron to eventually adopt its full adult function, its potential must be tightly regulated during development.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] As an organism progresses through development the resting membrane potential becomes more negative.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Glial cells are also differentiating and proliferating as development progresses in the brain.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The addition of these glial cells increases the organism's ability to regulate extracellular potassium.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The drop in extracellular potassium can lead to a decrease in membrane potential of 35 mV.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Cell excitability is the change in membrane potential that is necessary for cellular responses in various tissues.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Cell excitability is a property that is induced during early embryogenesis.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Excitability of a cell has also been defined as the ease with which a response may be triggered.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The resting and threshold potentials forms the basis of cell excitability and these processes are fundamental for the generation of graded and action potentials.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The most important regulators of cell excitability are the extracellular electrolyte concentrations (i.e.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Na+, K+, Ca2+, Cl−, Mg2+) and associated proteins.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Important proteins that regulate cell excitability are voltage-gated ion channels, ion transporters (e.g.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Na+/K+-ATPase, magnesium transporters, acid–base transporters), membrane receptors and hyperpolarization-activated cyclic-nucleotide-gated channels.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] For example, potassium channels and calcium-sensing receptors are important regulators of excitability in neurons, cardiac myocytes and many other excitable cells like astrocytes.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Calcium ion is also the most important second messenger in excitable cell signaling.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Activation of synaptic receptors initiates long-lasting changes in neuronal excitability.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Thyroid, adrenal and other hormones also regulate cell excitability, for example, progesterone and estrogen modulate myometrial smooth muscle cell excitability.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Many cell types are considered to have an excitable membrane.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Astrocytes display a form of non-electrical excitability based on intracellular calcium variations related to the expression of several receptors through which they can detect the synaptic signal.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] In neurons, there are different membrane properties in some portions of the cell, for example, dendritic excitability endows neurons with the capacity for coincidence detection of spatially separated inputs.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Electrophysiologists model the effects of ionic concentration differences, ion channels, and membrane capacitance in terms of an equivalent circuit, which is intended to represent the electrical properties of a small patch of membrane.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The equivalent circuit consists of a capacitor in parallel with four pathways each consisting of a battery in series with a variable conductance.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The capacitance is determined by the properties of the lipid bilayer, and is taken to be fixed.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Each of the four parallel pathways comes from one of the principal ions, sodium, potassium, chloride, and calcium.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The voltage of each ionic pathway is determined by the concentrations of the ion on each side of the membrane; see the Reversal potential section above.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The conductance of each ionic pathway at any point in time is determined by the states of all the ion channels that are potentially permeable to that ion, including leakage channels, ligand-gated channels, and voltage-gated ion channels.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] For fixed ion concentrations and fixed values of ion channel conductance, the equivalent circuit can be further reduced, using the Goldman equation as described below, to a circuit containing a capacitance in parallel with a battery and conductance.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] In electrical terms, this is a type of RC circuit (resistance-capacitance circuit), and its electrical properties are very simple.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Starting from any initial state, the current flowing across either the conductance or the capacitance decays with an exponential time course, with a time constant of τ = RC, where C is the capacitance of the membrane patch, and R = 1/gnet is the net resistance.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] For realistic situations, the time constant usually lies in the 1–100 millisecond range.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] In most cases, changes in the conductance of ion channels occur on a faster time scale, so an RC circuit is not a good approximation; however, the differential equation used to model a membrane patch is commonly a modified version of the RC circuit equation.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] When the membrane potential of a cell goes for a long period of time without changing significantly, it is referred to as a resting potential or resting voltage.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] This term is used for the membrane potential of non-excitable cells, but also for the membrane potential of excitable cells in the absence of excitation.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] In excitable cells, the other possible states are graded membrane potentials (of variable amplitude), and action potentials, which are large, all-or-nothing rises in membrane potential that usually follow a fixed time course.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Excitable cells include neurons, muscle cells, and some secretory cells in glands.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Even in other types of cells, however, the membrane voltage can undergo changes in response to environmental or intracellular stimuli.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] For example, depolarization of the plasma membrane appears to be an important step in programmed cell death.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The interactions that generate the resting potential are modeled by the Goldman equation.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] This is similar in form to the Nernst equation shown above, in that it is based on the charges of the ions in question, as well as the difference between their inside and outside concentrations.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] However, it also takes into consideration the relative permeability of the plasma membrane to each ion in question.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] In reality, there is some degree of permeability for several ions simultaneously, so the resting membrane potential is not the same as any one Nernst potential.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Rather, it is near a balance point of permeability for the prominent permeant ions (usually potassium, sodium, and chloride).
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] This can be represented by the Goldman-Hodgkin-Katz (GHK) voltage equation conceptually: ions with greater permeability contribute more to Vm.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] This is why the resting potential is typically close to EK (because PK is typically the largest at rest), but slightly positive compared to ENa depending on sodium leak and other electrical activity.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The three ions that appear in this equation are potassium (K+), sodium (Na+), and chloride (Cl−).
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Calcium is omitted, but can be added to deal with situations in which it plays a significant role.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Being an anion, the chloride terms are treated differently from the cation terms; the intracellular concentration is in the numerator, and the extracellular concentration in the denominator, which is reversed from the cation terms.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] *P*i stands for the relative permeability of the ion type i.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] In essence, the Goldman formula expresses the membrane potential as a weighted average of the reversal potentials for the individual ion types, weighted by permeability.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] (Although the membrane potential changes about 100 mV during an action potential, the concentrations of ions inside and outside the cell do not change significantly.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] They remain close to their respective concentrations when then membrane is at resting potential.) In most animal cells, the permeability to potassium is much higher in the resting state than the permeability to sodium.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] As a consequence, the resting potential is usually close to the potassium reversal potential.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The permeability to chloride can be high enough to be significant, but, unlike the other ions, chloride is not actively pumped, and therefore equilibrates at a reversal potential very close to the resting potential determined by the other ions.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Values of resting membrane potential in most animal cells usually vary between the potassium reversal potential (usually around −80 mV) and around −40 mV.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The resting potential in excitable cells (capable of producing action potentials) is usually near −60 mV—more depolarized voltages would lead to spontaneous generation of action potentials.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Immature or undifferentiated cells show highly variable values of resting voltage, usually significantly more positive than in differentiated cells.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] In such cells, the resting potential value correlates with the degree of differentiation: undifferentiated cells in some cases may not show any transmembrane voltage difference at all.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Maintenance of the resting potential can be metabolically costly for a cell because of its requirement for active pumping of ions to counteract losses due to leakage channels.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The cost is highest when the cell function requires an especially depolarized value of membrane voltage.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] For example, the resting potential in daylight-adapted blowfly (*Calliphora vicina*) photoreceptors can be as high as −30 mV.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] This elevated membrane potential allows the cells to respond very rapidly to visual inputs; the cost is that maintenance of the resting potential may consume more than 20% of overall cellular ATP.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] On the other hand, the high resting potential in undifferentiated cells does not necessarily incur a high metabolic cost.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] This apparent paradox is resolved by examination of the origin of that resting potential.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Little-differentiated cells are characterized by extremely high input resistance, which implies that few leakage channels are present at this stage of cell life.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] As an apparent result, potassium permeability becomes similar to that for sodium ions, which places resting potential in-between the reversal potentials for sodium and potassium as discussed above.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The reduced leakage currents also mean there is little need for active pumping in order to compensate, therefore low metabolic cost.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The classic approach is intracellular recording: one electrode is placed inside the cell and a reference electrode remains outside, allowing direct measurement of VmPerkins KL.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Cell-attached voltage-clamp and current-clamp recording and stimulation techniques in brain slices.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Modern electrophysiology frequently uses patch-clamp approaches, where a fine glass micropipette is pressed against the membrane to form a very high-resistance seal (giga-seal).
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] This seal isolates a tiny patch of membrane so researchers can record specific electrical signals and, depending on the configuration, control which side of the membrane is exposed to different solutions.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Voltage-clamp is useful for isolating sodium, potassium, calcium, or synaptic currents.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] As explained above, the potential at any point in a cell's membrane is determined by the ion concentration differences between the intracellular and extracellular areas, and by the permeability of the membrane to each type of ion.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The change in membrane potential can be either large or small, depending on how many ion channels are activated and what type they are, and can be either long or short, depending on the lengths of time that the channels remain open.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Changes of this type are referred to as **graded potentials**, in contrast to action potentials, which have a fixed amplitude and time course.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] As can be derived from the Goldman equation shown above, the effect of increasing the permeability of a membrane to a particular type of ion shifts the membrane potential toward the reversal potential for that ion.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Thus, opening Na+ channels shifts the membrane potential toward the Na+ reversal potential, which is usually around +100 mV.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Likewise, opening K+ channels shifts the membrane potential toward about −90 mV, and opening Cl− channels shifts it toward about −70 mV (resting potential of most membranes).
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Thus, Na+ channels shift the membrane potential in a positive direction, K+ channels shift it in a negative direction (except when the membrane is hyperpolarized to a value more negative than the K+ reversal potential), and Cl− channels tend to shift it towards the resting potential.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Graded membrane potentials are particularly important in neurons, where they are produced by synapses—a temporary change in membrane potential produced by activation of a synapse by a single graded or action potential is called a postsynaptic potential.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Neurotransmitters that act to open Na+ channels typically cause the membrane potential to become more positive, while neurotransmitters that activate K+ channels typically cause it to become more negative; those that inhibit these channels tend to have the opposite effect.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Whether a postsynaptic potential is considered excitatory or inhibitory depends on the reversal potential for the ions of that current, and the threshold for the cell to fire an action potential (around −50 mV).
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] A postsynaptic current with a reversal potential above threshold, such as a typical Na+ current, is considered excitatory.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] A current with a reversal potential below threshold, such as a typical K+ current, is considered inhibitory.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] A current with a reversal potential above the resting potential, but below threshold, will not by itself elicit action potentials, but will produce subthreshold membrane potential oscillations.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Thus, neurotransmitters that act to open Na+ channels produce excitatory postsynaptic potentials, or EPSPs, whereas neurotransmitters that act to open K+ or Cl− channels typically produce inhibitory postsynaptic potentials, or IPSPs.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] When multiple types of channels are open within the same time period, their postsynaptic potentials summate (are added together).
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] From the viewpoint of biophysics, the *resting* membrane potential is merely the membrane potential that results from the membrane permeabilities that predominate when the cell is resting.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The above equation of weighted averages always applies, but the following approach may be more easily visualized.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] If the driving force is high, then the ion is being "pushed" across the membrane.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] If the permeability is high, it will be easier for the ion to diffuse across the membrane.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] So, in a resting membrane, while the driving force for potassium is low, its permeability is very high.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Sodium has a huge driving force but almost no resting permeability.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] In this case, potassium carries about 20 times more current than sodium, and thus has 20 times more influence over *E*m than does sodium.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] However, consider another case—the peak of the action potential.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Here, permeability to Na is high and K permeability is relatively low.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Thus, the membrane moves to near *E*Na and far from *E*K.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The more ions are permeant the more complicated it becomes to predict the membrane potential.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] However, this can be done using the Goldman-Hodgkin-Katz equation or the weighted means equation.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] By plugging in the concentration gradients and the permeabilities of the ions at any instant in time, one can determine the membrane potential at that moment.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] What the GHK equations means is that, at any time, the value of the membrane potential will be a weighted average of the equilibrium potentials of all permeant ions.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The "weighting" is the ions relative permeability across the membrane.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] While cells expend energy to transport ions and establish a transmembrane potential, they use this potential in turn to transport other ions and metabolites such as sugar.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] The transmembrane potential of the mitochondria drives the production of ATP, which is the common currency of biological energy.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Cells may draw on the energy they store in the resting potential to drive action potentials or other forms of excitation.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] These changes in the membrane potential enable communication with other cells (as with action potentials) or initiate changes inside the cell, which happens in an egg when it is fertilized by a sperm.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Changes in the dielectric properties of plasma membrane may act as hallmark of underlying conditions such as diabetes and dyslipidemia.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] In neuronal cells, an action potential begins with a rush of sodium ions into the cell through sodium channels, resulting in depolarization, while recovery involves an outward rush of potassium through potassium channels.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] Both of these fluxes occur by passive diffusion.
[src:action-potential/membrane-potential] A dose of salt may trigger the still-working neurons of a fresh cut of meat into firing, causing muscle spasms.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] The relatively static membrane potential of quiescent cells is called the **resting membrane potential** (or resting voltage), as opposed to the specific dynamic electrochemical phenomena called action potential and graded membrane potential.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] The **resting membrane potential** has a value of approximately **−70 mV or −0.07 V**.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] Apart from the latter two, which occur in excitable cells (neurons, muscles, and some secretory cells in glands), membrane voltage in the majority of non-excitable cells can also undergo changes in response to environmental or intracellular stimuli.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] The resting potential exists due to the differences in membrane permeabilities for potassium, sodium, calcium, and chloride ions, which in turn result from functional activity of various ion channels, ion transporters, and exchangers.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] Conventionally, resting membrane potential can be defined as a relatively stable, ground value of transmembrane voltage in animal and plant cells.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] Again, because of the high relative permeability for potassium, the resulting membrane potential is almost always close to the potassium reversal potential.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] But in order for this process to occur, a concentration gradient of potassium ions must first be set up.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] This work is done by the ion pumps/transporters and/or exchangers and generally is powered by ATP.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] In the case of the resting membrane potential across an animal cell's plasma membrane, potassium (and sodium) gradients are established by the Na+/K+-ATPase (sodium-potassium pump) which transports 2 potassium ions inside and 3 sodium ions outside at the cost of 1 ATP molecule.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] In other cases, for example, a membrane potential may be established by acidification of the inside of a membranous compartment (such as the proton pump that generates membrane potential across synaptic vesicle membranes).
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] In most quantitative treatments of membrane potential, such as the derivation of Goldman equation, **electroneutrality** is assumed; that is, that there is no measurable charge excess on either side of the membrane.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] That occurs because the effect of charge on electrochemical potential is hugely greater than the effect of concentration so an undetectable change in concentration creates a great change in electric potential.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] Cell membranes are typically permeable to only a subset of ions.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] These usually include potassium ions, chloride ions, bicarbonate ions, and others.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] To simplify the description of the ionic basis of the resting membrane potential, it is most useful to consider only one ionic species at first, and consider the others later.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] Since trans-plasma-membrane potentials are almost always determined primarily by potassium permeability, that is where to start.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] H+ exporting ATPase render the membrane voltage in plants and fungi much more negative than in the more extensively investigated animal cells, where the resting voltage is mainly determined by selective ion channels.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] In most neurons the resting potential has a value of approximately −70 mV.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] The resting potential is mostly determined by the concentrations of the ions in the fluids on both sides of the cell membrane and the ion transport proteins that are in the cell membrane.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] How the concentrations of ions and the membrane transport proteins influence the value of the resting potential is outlined below.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] The resting potential of a cell can be most thoroughly understood by thinking of it in terms of equilibrium potentials.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] In the example diagram here, the model cell was given only one permeant ion (potassium).
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] In this case, the resting potential of this cell would be the same as the equilibrium potential for potassium.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] However, a real cell is more complicated, having permeabilities to many ions, each of which contributes to the resting potential.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] To understand better, consider a cell with only two permeant ions, potassium, and sodium.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] Consider a case where these two ions have equal concentration gradients directed in opposite directions, and that the membrane permeabilities to both ions are equal.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] K+ leaving the cell will tend to drag the membrane potential toward *E*K.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] Na+ entering the cell will tend to drag the membrane potential toward the reversal potential for sodium *E*Na.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] Since the permeabilities to both ions were set to be equal, the membrane potential will, at the end of the Na+/K+ tug-of-war, end up halfway between *E*Na and *E*K.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] As *E*Na and *E*K were equal but of opposite signs, halfway in between is zero, meaning that the membrane will rest at 0 mV.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] Note that even though the membrane potential at 0 mV is stable, it is not an equilibrium condition because neither of the contributing ions is in equilibrium.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] Ions diffuse down their electrochemical gradients through ion channels, but the membrane potential is upheld by continual K+ influx and Na+ efflux via ion transporters.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] Such situation with similar permeabilities for counter-acting ions, like potassium and sodium in animal cells, can be extremely costly for the cell if these permeabilities are relatively large, as it takes a lot of ATP energy to pump the ions back.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] Because no real cell can afford such equal and large ionic permeabilities at rest, resting potential of animal cells is determined by predominant high permeability to potassium and adjusted to the required value by modulating sodium and chloride permeabilities and gradients.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] In a healthy animal cell Na+ permeability is about 5% of the K+ permeability or even less, whereas the respective reversal potentials are +60 mV for sodium (*E*Na)and −80 mV for potassium (*E*K).
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] Thus the membrane potential will not be right at *E*K, but rather depolarized from *E*K by an amount of approximately 5% of the 140 mV difference between *E*K and *E*Na.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] Thus, the cell's resting potential will be about −73 mV.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] In a more formal notation, the membrane potential is the weighted average of each contributing ion's equilibrium potential.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] The size of each weight is the relative conductance of each ion.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] For determination of membrane potentials, the two most important types of membrane ion transport proteins are ion channels and ion transporters.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] Ion channel proteins create paths across cell membranes through which ions can passively diffuse without direct expenditure of metabolic energy.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] They have selectivity for certain ions, thus, there are potassium-, chloride-, and sodium-selective ion channels.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] Different cells and even different parts of one cell (dendrites, cell bodies, nodes of Ranvier) will have different amounts of various ion transport proteins.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] Typically, the amount of certain potassium channels is most important for control of the resting potential (see below).
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] Some ion pumps such as the Na+/K+-ATPase are electrogenic, that is, they produce charge imbalance across the cell membrane and can also contribute directly to the membrane potential.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] Most pumps use metabolic energy (ATP) to function.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] For most animal cells potassium ions (K+) are the most important for the resting potential.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] Due to the active transport of potassium ions, the concentration of potassium is higher inside cells than outside.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] Most cells have potassium-selective ion channel proteins that remain open all the time.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] There will be net movement of positively charged potassium ions through these potassium channels with a resulting accumulation of excess negative charge inside of the cell.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] "Balance" means that the electrical force (potential) that results from the build-up of ionic charge, and which impedes outward diffusion, increases until it is equal in magnitude but opposite in direction to the tendency for outward diffusive movement of potassium.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] This balance point is an *equilibrium potential* as the net transmembrane flux (or current) of K+ is zero.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] A good approximation for the equilibrium potential of a given ion only needs the concentrations on either side of the membrane and the temperature.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] Potassium equilibrium potentials of around −80 millivolts (inside negative) are common.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] Differences are observed in different species, different tissues within the same animal, and the same tissues under different environmental conditions.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] Applying the Nernst Equation above, one may account for these differences by changes in relative K+ concentration or differences in temperature.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] For common usage the Nernst equation is often given in a simplified form by assuming typical human body temperature (37 °C), reducing the constants and switching to Log base 10.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] (The units used for concentration are unimportant as they will cancel out into a ratio).
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] Likewise the equilibrium potential for sodium (Na+) at normal human body temperature is calculated using the same simplified constant.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] You can calculate E assuming an outside concentration, [K+]o, of 10mM and an inside concentration, [K+]i, of 100mM.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] For chloride ions (Cl−) the sign of the constant must be reversed (−61.54 mV).
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] If calculating the equilibrium potential for calcium (Ca2+) the 2+ charge halves the simplified constant to 30.77 mV.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] If working at room temperature, about 21 °C, the calculated constants are approximately 58 mV for K+ and Na+, −58 mV for Cl− and 29 mV for Ca2+.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] At physiological temperature, about 29.5 °C, and physiological concentrations (which vary for each ion), the calculated potentials are approximately 67 mV for Na+, −90 mV for K+, −86 mV for Cl− and 123 mV for Ca2+.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] The resting membrane potential is not an equilibrium potential as it relies on the constant expenditure of energy (for ionic pumps as mentioned above) for its maintenance.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] It is a dynamic diffusion potential that takes this mechanism into account—wholly unlike the pillows equilibrium potential, which is true no matter the nature of the system under consideration.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] The resting membrane potential is dominated by the ionic species in the system that has the greatest conductance across the membrane.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] As potassium is also the ion with the most negative equilibrium potential, usually the resting potential can be no more negative than the potassium equilibrium potential.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] The resting potential can be calculated with the Goldman-Hodgkin-Katz voltage equation using the concentrations of ions as for the equilibrium potential while also including the relative permeabilities of each ionic species.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] This equation resembles the Nernst equation, but has a term for each permeant ion.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] Also, *z* has been inserted into the equation, causing the intracellular and extracellular concentrations of Cl− to be reversed relative to K+ and Na+, as chloride's negative charge is handled by inverting the fraction inside the logarithmic term.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] where *g*tot is the combined conductance of all ionic species, again in arbitrary units.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] The latter equation portrays the resting membrane potential as a *weighted average* of the reversal potentials of the system, where the weights are the relative conductances of each ion species (*g*X/*g*tot).
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] During the action potential, these weights change.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] If the conductances of Na+ and Cl− are zero, the membrane potential reduces to the Nernst potential for K+ (as *g*K+ = *g*tot).
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] Normally, under resting conditions *g*Na+ and *g*Cl− are not zero, but they are much smaller than *g*K+, which renders *E*m close to *E*eq,K+.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] Medical conditions such as hyperkalemia in which blood serum potassium (which governs [K+]o) is changed are very dangerous since they offset *E*eq,K+, thus affecting *E*m.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] This may cause arrhythmias and cardiac arrest.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] Although the GHK voltage equation and Millman's equation are related, they are not equivalent.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] The critical difference is that Millman's equation assumes the current-voltage relationship to be ohmic, whereas the GHK voltage equation takes into consideration the small, instantaneous rectifications predicted by the GHK flux equation caused by the concentration gradient of ions.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] Thus, a more accurate estimate of membrane potential can be calculated using the GHK equation than with Millman's equation.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] In some cells, the membrane potential is always changing (such as cardiac pacemaker cells).
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] For such cells there is never any "rest" and the "resting potential" is a theoretical concept.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] Other cells with little in the way of membrane transport functions that change with time have a resting membrane potential that can be measured by inserting an electrode into the cell.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] Transmembrane potentials can also be measured optically with dyes that change their optical properties according to the membrane potential.
[src:action-potential/resting-potential] Resting currents in nerves were measured and described by Julius Bernstein in 1902 where he proposed a "Membrane Theory" that explained the resting potential of nerve and muscle as a diffusion potential.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] In excitable cells (such as neurons, myocytes, and certain types of glia), sodium channels enable the rising phase of action potentials.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] These channels go through three different states: resting, active, and inactive.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Even though the resting and inactive states do not allow ions to flow through the channels, the difference exists with respect to their structural conformation.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Sodium channels are highly selective for transporting sodium ions across cell membranes.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] The high selectivity with respect to the sodium ion is achieved in many different ways.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] All involve encapsulating the sodium ion in a cavity of specific size within a larger molecule.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Sodium channels consist of large alpha subunits that associate with accessory proteins, such as beta subunits.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] An alpha subunit forms the core of the channel and is functional on its own.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] When the alpha subunit protein is expressed by a cell, it is able to form a pore in the cell membrane that conducts Na+ in a voltage-dependent way, even if beta subunits or other known modulating proteins are not expressed.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] When accessory proteins assemble with α subunits, the resulting complex can display altered voltage dependence and cellular localization.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] The alpha subunit consists of four repeat domains, labelled I through IV, each containing six membrane-spanning segments, labelled S1 through S6.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] The highly conserved S4 segment acts as the channel's voltage sensor.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] The voltage sensitivity of this channel is due to positive amino acids located at every third position.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] When stimulated by a change in transmembrane voltage, this segment moves toward the extracellular side of the cell membrane, allowing the channel to become permeable to ions.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] The ions are conducted through the central pore cavity, which consists of two main regions.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] The more external (i.e., more extracellular) portion of the pore is formed by the "P-loops" (the region between S5 and S6) of the four domains.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] This region is the most narrow part of the pore and is responsible for its ion selectivity.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] The inner portion (i.e., more cytoplasmic) of the pore is the pore gate and is formed by the combined S5 and S6 segments of the four domains.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] The pore domain also features lateral tunnels or fenestrations that run perpendicular to the pore axis.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] These fenestrations that connect the central cavity to the membrane are proposed to be important for drug accessibility.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] In mammalian sodium channels, the region linking domains III and IV is also important for channel function.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] This DIII-IV linker is responsible for wedging the pore gate shut after channel opening, inactivating it.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Voltage-gated Na+ channels have three main conformational states: closed, open and inactivated.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Closed and inactivated states are ion impermeable.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Before an action potential occurs, the axonal membrane is at its normal resting potential, about −70 mV in most human neurons, and Na+ channels are in their deactivated state, blocked on the extracellular side by their **activation gates**.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Because the voltage across the membrane is initially negative, as its voltage increases *to* and *past* zero (from −70 mV at rest to a maximum of +30 mV), it is said to depolarize.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] This increase in voltage constitutes the rising phase of an action potential.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] At the peak of the action potential, when enough Na+ has entered the neuron and the membrane's potential has become high enough, the Na+ channels inactivate themselves by closing their **inactivation gates**.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] The inactivation gate can be thought of as a "plug" tethered to domains III and IV of the channel's intracellular alpha subunit.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Closure of the inactivation gate causes Na+ flow through the channel to stop, which in turn causes the membrane potential to stop rising.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] The closing of the inactivation gate creates a refractory period within each individual Na+ channel.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] This refractory period eliminates the possibility of an action potential moving in the opposite direction back towards the soma.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] With its inactivation gate closed, the channel is said to be inactivated.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] With the Na+ channel no longer contributing to the membrane potential, the potential decreases back to its resting potential as the neuron repolarizes and subsequently hyperpolarizes itself, and this constitutes the falling phase of an action potential.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] The refractory period of each channel is therefore vital in propagating the action potential unidirectionally down an axon for proper communication between neurons.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] When the membrane's voltage becomes low enough, the inactivation gate reopens and the activation gate closes in a process called **deinactivation**.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] With the activation gate closed and the inactivation gate open, the Na+ channel is once again in its deactivated state, and is ready to participate in another action potential.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] When any kind of ion channel does not inactivate itself, it is said to be persistently (or tonically) active.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Some kinds of ion channels are naturally persistently active.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] However, genetic mutations that cause persistent activity in other channels can cause disease by creating excessive activity of certain kinds of neurons.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Mutations that interfere with Na+ channel inactivation can contribute to cardiovascular diseases or epileptic seizures by **window currents**, which can cause muscle and/or nerve cells to become over-excited.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] The temporal behavior of Na+ channels can be modeled by a Markovian scheme or by the Hodgkin–Huxley-type formalism.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] In the former scheme, each channel occupies a distinct state with differential equations describing transitions between states; in the latter, the channels are treated as a population that are affected by three independent gating variables.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Each of these variables can attain a value between 1 (fully permeant to ions) and 0 (fully non-permeant), the product of these variables yielding the percentage of conducting channels.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] The Hodgkin–Huxley model can be shown to be equivalent to a Markovian model.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] The pore of sodium channels contains a selectivity filter made of negatively charged amino acid residues, which attract the positive Na+ ion and keep out negatively charged ions such as chloride.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] The cations flow into a more constricted part of the pore that is 0.3 by 0.5 nm wide, which is just large enough to allow a single Na+ ion with a water molecule associated to pass through.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] The larger K+ ion cannot fit through this area.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Ions of different sizes also cannot interact as well with the negatively charged glutamic acid residues that line the pore.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Voltage-gated sodium channels normally consist of an alpha subunit that forms the ion conduction pore and one to two beta subunits that have several functions including modulation of channel gating.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Expression of the alpha subunit alone is sufficient to produce a functional channel.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] The family of sodium channels has 9 known members, with amino acid identity >50% in the trans-membrane segments and extracellular loop regions.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] A standardized nomenclature for sodium channels is currently used and is maintained by the IUPHAR.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] The proteins of these channels are named Nav1.1 through Nav1.9.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] The gene names are referred to as SCN1A through SCN5A, then SCN8A through SCN11A.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] The "tenth member", Nax, does not act in a voltage-gated way.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] It has a loosely similar overall structure.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Not much is known about its real function, other than that it also associates with beta subunits.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] The probable evolutionary relationship between these channels, based on the similarity of their amino acid sequences, is shown in figure 1.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] The individual sodium channels are distinguished not only by differences in their sequence but also by their kinetics and expression profiles.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Some of this data is summarized in table 1, below.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Sodium channel beta subunits are type 1 transmembrane glycoproteins with an extracellular N-terminus and a cytoplasmic C-terminus.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] As members of the Ig superfamily, beta subunits contain a prototypic V-set Ig loop in their extracellular domain.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] They do not share any homology with their counterparts of calcium and potassium channels.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Instead, they are homologous to neural cell adhesion molecules (CAMs) and the large family of L1 CAMs.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] There are four distinct betas named in order of discovery: SCN1B, SCN2B, SCN3B, SCN4B (table 2).
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Beta 1 and beta 3 interact with the alpha subunit non-covalently, whereas beta 2 and beta 4 associate with alpha via disulfide bond.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Sodium channels are more likely to stay open at the subthreshold membrane potential when interacting with beta toxins, which in turn induces an immediate sensation of pain.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] In addition to regulating channel gating, sodium channel beta subunits also modulate channel expression and form links to the intracellular cytoskeleton via ankyrin and spectrin.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Voltage-gated sodium channels also assemble with a variety of other proteins, such as FHF proteins (Fibroblast growth factor Homologous Factor), calmodulin, cytoskeleton or regulatory kinases, which form a complex with sodium channels, influencing its expression and/or function.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Several beta subunits interact with one or more extracellular matrix (ECM) molecules.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Contactin, also known as F3 or F11, associates with beta 1 as shown via co-immunoprecipitation.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Fibronectin-like (FN-like) repeats of Tenascin-C and Tenascin-R bind with beta 2 in contrast to the Epidermal growth factor-like (EGF-like) repeats that repel beta2.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] A disintegrin and metalloproteinase (ADAM) 10 sheds beta 2's ectodomain possibly inducing neurite outgrowth.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Beta 3 and beta 1 bind to neurofascin at Nodes of Ranvier in developing neurons.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Ligand-gated sodium channels are activated by binding of a ligand instead of a change in membrane potential.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] They are found, e.g. in the neuromuscular junction as nicotinic receptors, where the ligands are acetylcholine molecules.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Most channels of this type are permeable to potassium to some degree as well as to sodium.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Voltage-gated sodium channels play an important role in action potentials.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] If enough channels open when there is a change in the cell's membrane potential, a small but significant number of Na+ ions will move into the cell down their electrochemical gradient, further depolarizing the cell.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Thus, the more Na+ channels localized in a region of a cell's membrane the faster the action potential will propagate and the more **excitable** that area of the cell will be.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] This is an example of a positive feedback loop.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] The ability of these channels to assume a closed-inactivated state causes the refractory period and is critical for the propagation of action potentials down an axon.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Na+ channels both open and close more quickly than K+ channels, producing an influx of positive charge (Na+) toward the beginning of the action potential and an efflux (K+) toward the end.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Ligand-gated sodium channels, on the other hand, create the change in the membrane potential in the first place, in response to the binding of a ligand to it.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Leak sodium channels additionally contribute to action potential regulation by modulating the resting potential (and in turn, the excitability) of a cell.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Sodium leak channels do not show any voltage or ligand gating.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Instead, they are always open or "leaking" a small background current to regulate the resting membrane potential of a neuron.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] In most animals, a single gene encodes the NALCN (sodium leak channel, nonselective) protein.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Despite following the same basic structure as other sodium channels, NALCN is not sensitive to voltage changes.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] The voltage-sensitive S4 transmembrane domain of NALCN has fewer positively charged amino acids (13 instead of a voltage gated channel's 21) possibly explaining its voltage insensitivity.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] NALCN is also far less selective for Na+ ions and is permeable to Ca2+ and K+ ions.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] The EEKE amino acid motif in the pore filter domain of NALCN is similar to both the EEEE motif of voltage-gated calcium channel and the DEKA motif of the voltage-gated sodium channel, possibly explaining its lack of selectivity.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] NALCN is not blocked by many common sodium channel blockers, including tetrodotoxin.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] NALCN is blocked nonspecifically by both Gd3+ and verapamil.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Substance P and neurotensin both activate Src family kinases through their respective GPCRs (independent of the coupled G-proteins) which in turn increase the permeability of NALCN through UNC80 activation.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Acetylcholine can also increase NALCN activity through M3 muscarinic acetylcholine receptors.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Higher levels of extracellular Ca2+ decrease the permeability of NALCN by activating CaSR which inhibits UNC80.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] NALCN complexes with the proteins UNC79, UNC80, and FAM155A.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] UNC79 appears to be linked to membrane stability of NALCN and linkage with UNC 80.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] UNC80 mediates chemical modulation of NALCN through multiple pathways.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] FAM155A helps protein folding in the endoplasmic reticulum, chaperones transport to the axon, and contributes to membrane stability.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] The resting membrane potential of a neuron is usually -60mV to -80mV, driven primarily by the K+ potential at -90mV.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] The depolarization from the K+ potential is due primarily to a small Na+ leak current.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] About 70% of this current is through NALCN.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Increasing NALCN permeability lowers the resting membrane potential, bringing it closer to the trigger of an action potential (-55mV), thus increasing the excitability of a neuron.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Mutations to NALCN lead to severe disruptions to respiratory rhythm in mice and altered circadian locomotion in flies.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Mutations to NALCN have also been linked to multiple severe developmental disorders and cervical dystonia.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Schizophrenia and bipolar disorder are also linked to mutations to NALCN.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Changes in blood and tissue pH accompany physiological and pathophysiological conditions such as exercise, cardiac ischemia, ischemic stroke, and cocaine ingestion.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] These conditions are known to trigger the symptoms of electrical diseases in patients carrying sodium channel mutations.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Protons cause a diverse set of changes to sodium channel gating, which generally lead to decreases in the amplitude of the transient sodium current and increases in the fraction of non-inactivating channels that pass persistent currents.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] These effects are shared with disease-causing mutants in neuronal, skeletal muscle, and cardiac tissue.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] And they may be compounded in mutants that impart greater proton sensitivity to sodium channels, suggesting a role of protons in triggering acute symptoms of electrical disease.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Single channel data from cardiomyocytes have shown that protons can decrease the conductance of individual sodium channels.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] The sodium channel selectivity filter is composed of a single residue in each of the four pore-loops of the four functional domains.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] These four residues are known as the DEKA motif.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] The permeation rate of sodium through the sodium channel is determined by a four carboxylate residues, the EEDD motif, which make up the outer charged ring.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] The protonation of these carboxylates is one of the main drivers of proton block in sodium channels, although there are other residues that also contribute to pH sensitivity.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] One such residue is C373 in the cardiac sodium channel which makes it the most pH-sensitive sodium channel among the sodium channels that have been studied to date.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] As the cardiac sodium channel is the most pH-sensitive sodium channel, most of what is known is based on this channel.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Reduction in extracellular pH has been shown to depolarize the voltage-dependence of activation and inactivation to more positive potentials.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] This indicates that during activities that decrease the blood pH, such as exercising, the probability of channels activating and inactivating is higher more positive membrane potentials, which can lead to potential adverse effects.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] The sodium channels expressed in skeletal muscle fibers have evolved into relatively pH-insensitive channels.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] This has been suggested to be a protective mechanism against potential over- or under-excitability in skeletal muscles, as blood pH levels are highly susceptible to change during movement.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Recently, a mixed syndrome mutation that causes periodic paralysis and myotonia in the skeletal sodium channel has been shown to impart pH-sensitivity in this channel, making the gating of this channel similar to that of the cardiac subtype.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] The effects of protonation have been characterized in Nav1.1–Nav1.5.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Among these channels, Nav1.1–Nav1.3 and Nav1.5 display depolarized voltage-dependence of activation, while activation in Nav1.4 remains insensitive to acidosis.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] The voltage-dependence of steady-state fast inactivation is unchanged in Nav1.1–Nav1.4, but steady-state fast inactivation in Nav1.5 is depolarized.
[src:action-potential/sodium-channel] Hence, among the sodium channels that have been studied so far, Nav1.4 is the least and Nav1.5 is the most proton-sensitive subtypes.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] Voltage-gated ion channels have a crucial role in excitable cells such as neuronal and muscle tissues, allowing a rapid and co-ordinated depolarization in response to triggering voltage change.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] Found along the axon and at the synapse, voltage-gated ion channels directionally propagate electrical signals.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] Voltage-gated ion-channels are usually ion-specific, and channels specific to sodium (Na+), potassium (K+), calcium (Ca2+), and chloride (Cl−) ions have been identified.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] The opening and closing of the channels are triggered by changing ion concentration, and hence charge gradient, between the sides of the cell membrane.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] Voltage-gated ion channels are generally composed of several subunits arranged in such a way that there is a central pore through which ions can travel down their electrochemical gradients.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] The channels tend to be ion-specific, although similarly sized and charged ions may sometimes travel through them.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] The functionality of voltage-gated ion channels is attributed to its three main discrete units: the voltage sensor, the pore or conducting pathway, and the gate.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] Na+, K+, and Ca2+ channels are composed of four transmembrane domains arranged around a central pore; these four domains are part of a single α-subunit in the case of most Na+ and Ca2+ channels, whereas there are four α-subunits, each contributing one transmembrane domain, in most K+ channels.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] The membrane-spanning segments, designated S1-S6, are all alpha helices with specialized functions.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] The fifth and sixth transmembrane segments (S5 and S6) and pore loop serve the principal role of ion conduction, comprising the gate and pore of the channel, while S1-S4 serve as the voltage-sensing region.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] The four subunits may be identical, or different from one another.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] In addition to the four central α-subunits, there are also regulatory β-subunits, with oxidoreductase activity, which are located on the inner surface of the cell membrane and do not cross the membrane, and which are coassembled with the α-subunits in the endoplasmic reticulum.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] Crystallographic structural studies of a potassium channel have shown that, when a potential difference is introduced over the membrane, the associated electric field induces a conformational change in the potassium channel.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] The conformational change distorts the shape of the channel proteins sufficiently such that the cavity, or channel, opens to allow influx or efflux to occur across the membrane.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] This movement of ions down their concentration gradients subsequently generates an electric current sufficient to depolarize the cell membrane.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] Voltage-gated sodium channels and calcium channels are made up of a single polypeptide with four homologous domains.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] Each domain contains 6 membrane spanning alpha helices.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] One of these helices, S4, is the voltage sensing helix.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] The S4 segment contains many positive charges such that a high positive charge outside the cell repels the helix, keeping the channel in its closed state.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] In general, the voltage sensing portion of the ion channel is responsible for the detection of changes in transmembrane potential that trigger the opening or closing of the channel.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] The S1-4 alpha helices are generally thought to serve this role.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] In potassium and sodium channels, voltage-sensing S4 helices contain positively-charged lysine or arginine residues in repeated motifs.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] In its resting state, half of each S4 helix is in contact with the cell cytosol.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] Upon depolarization, the positively-charged residues on the S4 domains move toward the exoplasmic surface of the membrane.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] It is thought that the first 4 arginines account for the gating current, moving toward the extracellular solvent upon channel activation in response to membrane depolarization.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] The movement of 10–12 of these protein-bound positive charges triggers a conformational change that opens the channel.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] Movement of the voltage-sensor triggers a conformational change of the gate of the conducting pathway, controlling the flow of ions through the channel.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] The exact mechanism by which this movement occurs is not currently agreed upon, however the canonical, transporter, paddle, and twisted models are examples of current theories.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] The canonical model is also known as the sliding-helix model.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] The model suggests that when the plasma membrane becomes depolarized, the S4 helix shifts outward via either a proteinaceous vestibule or canaliculus by slide or screw like motion.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] Therefore, the positive charges of the arginine side chain changes position from an inward water pocket to an outward pocket due to the transposition of S4.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] The main functional part of the voltage-sensitive protein domain of these channels generally contains a region composed of S3b and S4 helices, known as the "paddle" due to its shape, which appears to be a conserved sequence, interchangeable across a wide variety of cells and species.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] A similar voltage sensor paddle has also been found in a family of voltage sensitive phosphatases in various species.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] Genetic engineering of the paddle region from a species of volcano-dwelling archaebacteria into rat brain potassium channels results in a fully functional ion channel, as long as the whole intact paddle is replaced.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] This "modularity" allows use of simple and inexpensive model systems to study the function of this region, its role in disease, and pharmaceutical control of its behavior rather than being limited to poorly characterized, expensive, and/or difficult to study preparations.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] Although voltage-gated ion channels are typically activated by membrane depolarization, some channels, such as inward-rectifier potassium ion channels, are activated instead by hyperpolarization.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] The gate is thought to be coupled to the voltage sensing regions of the channels and appears to contain a mechanical obstruction to ion flow.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] While the S6 domain has been agreed upon as the segment acting as this obstruction, its exact mechanism is unknown.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] Possible explanations include: the S6 segment makes a scissor-like movement allowing ions to flow through, the S6 segment breaks into two segments allowing of passing of ions through the channel, or the S6 channel serving as the gate itself.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] The mechanism by which the movement of the S4 segment affects that of S6 is still unknown, however it is theorized that there is a S4-S5 linker whose movement allows the opening of S6.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] Inactivation of ion channels occurs within milliseconds after opening.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] Inactivation is thought to be mediated by an intracellular gate that controls the opening of the pore on the inside of the cell.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] This gate is modeled as a ball tethered to a flexible chain.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] During inactivation, the chain folds in on itself and the ball blocks the flow of ions through the channel.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] Fast inactivation is directly linked to the activation caused by intramembrane movements of the S4 segments, though the mechanism linking movement of S4 and the engagement of the inactivation gate is unknown.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] Sodium channels have similar functional properties across many different cell types.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] While ten human genes encoding for sodium channels have been identified, their function is typically conserved between species and different cell types.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] With sixteen different identified genes for human calcium channels, this type of channel differs in function between cell types.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] Ca2+ channels produce action potentials similarly to Na+ channels in some neurons.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] They also play a role in neurotransmitter release in pre-synaptic nerve endings.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] In most cells, Ca2+ channels regulate a wide variety of biochemical processes due to their role in controlling intracellular Ca2+ concentrations.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] Potassium channels are the largest and most diverse class of voltage-gated channels, with over 100 encoding human genes.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] These types of channels differ significantly in their gating properties; some inactivating extremely slowly and others inactivating extremely quickly.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] This difference in activation time influences the duration and rate of action potential firing, which has a significant effect on electrical conduction along an axon as well as synaptic transmission.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] Potassium channels differ in structure from the other channels in that they contain four separate polypeptide subunits, while the other channels contain four homologous domain but on a single polypeptide unit.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] Chloride channels are present in all types of neurons.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] With the chief responsibility of controlling excitability, chloride channels contribute to the maintenance of cell resting potential and help to regulate cell volume.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] Voltage-gated proton channels carry currents mediated by hydrogen ions in the form of hydronium, and are activated by depolarization in a pH-dependent manner.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] They function to remove acid from cells.
[src:action-potential/voltage-gated-ion-channel] Phylogenetic studies of proteins expressed in bacteria revealed the existence of a superfamily of voltage-gated sodium channels.
